{"title_page": "Screen time", "text_new": "{{Other uses|Screen time (disambiguation)}}\n{{See also|Digital media use and mental health|Gaming disorder|Mobile phone overuse}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n\n'''Screen time''' is the amount of time spent using a device with a [[Display device|screen]] such as a [[smartphone]], computer, television, or [[video game console]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/screen+time|title=Definition of SCREEN TIME|website=www.merriam-webster.com|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> The concept is under significant research with related concepts in [[digital media use and mental health]]. Studies show that screen time directly impacts child development, and mental and physical health.<ref name=\"Stiglic e023191\">{{cite journal |last1=Stiglic |first1=Neza |last2=Viner |first2=Russell M |title=Effects of screentime on the health and well-being of children and adolescents: a systematic review of reviews |journal=BMJ Open |date=3 January 2019 |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=e023191 |doi=10.1136/bmjopen-2018-023191 |pmid=30606703 |pmc=6326346 }}</ref> The positive or negative health effects or screen time are influenced by levels and content of exposure. To prevent harmful exposure to screen time, some governments have placed regulations on its usage.<ref name=\":5\" /> \n[[File:Screen time.jpg|thumb|People using phones whilst walking]]\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Statistics ===\nThe first electronic screen was the cathode ray tube (CRT), which was invented in 1897 and commercialized in 1922.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal |title=The Cathode Ray Tube and its Applications |journal=Nature |date=July 1942 |volume=150 |issue=3794 |pages=74 |doi=10.1038/150074d0 |bibcode=1942Natur.150S..74. }}</ref> CRT\u2019s were the most popular choice for display screens until the rise of liquid crystal displays (LCDs) in the early 2000s.<ref name=\":1\" /> Screens are now an essential part of entertainment, advertising, and information technologies.\n\nSince their popularization in 2007, smartphones have become ubiquitous in daily life. In 2015, 64% of all American adults reported owning a smartphone, including 85% of individuals between 18 and 29 years old.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pewresearch.org/internet/2015/04/01/us-smartphone-use-in-2015/|title=U.S. Smartphone Use in 2015|last=NW|first=1615 L. St|last2=Suite 800Washington|date=2015-04-01|website=Pew Research Center: Internet, Science & Tech|access-date=2019-11-09|last3=Inquiries|first3=DC 20036USA202-419-4300 {{!}} Main202-857-8562 {{!}} Fax202-419-4372 {{!}} Media}}</ref> An American survey found a median of 3.7 minutes per hour of screen time over a 30 day period.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nAll forms of screens are most frequently used by younger age brackets, particularly young children. 98.5% of surveyed children aged 12\u201315 reported daily TV use and 91.1% reported daily computer use over a period of 30 days.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo68061|title=TV watching and computer use in U.S. youth aged 12-15, 2012|last=Herrick|first=Kirsten A|last2=Fakhouri|first2=Tala H. I|last3=Carlson|first3=Susan A|last4=Fulton|first4=Janet E|last5=National Center for Health Statistics (U.S.)|date=2014|language=English|oclc=897600869}}</ref>\n\n=== Race, socioeconomic class, and screen time ===\nResearch has shown that race and socioeconomic class are associated with overall screen time. Younger demographics and individuals who self-identified as Black and \"Other\" were associated with above average screen use.<ref name=\":2\" /> Additionally, Black and Latino Americans had longer screen times because of less access to desktop computers, which thus leads to more time on phones.<ref name=\":2\" /> In children, the divide is much larger. One average white children spend 8.5 hours a day with digital media, and Black and Latino children spend about 13 hours a day on screens.<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://dcmp.org/learn/301-children-media-and-race-media-use-among-white-black-hispanic-and-asian-american-children|title=Children, Media, and Race: Media Use Among White, Black, Hispanic, and Asian American Children|website=dcmp.org|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\u00a0Black and Latino children are also more likely to have TVs in their rooms, which contributes to their increased use of screen time.<ref name=\":19\" />\n\nThe discrepancy in the amount of screen time can also be attributed to a difference in income.\u00a0 In more affluent private schools, there has been a larger push to remove screens from education in order to limit the negative impacts that have been found from screen time.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/26/style/digital-divide-screens-schools.html|title=The Digital Gap Between Rich and Poor Kids Is Not What We Expected|last=Bowles|first=Nellie|date=2018-10-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-09|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> However, in public schools there is more push for the use of technology with some public schools advertising free iPads and laptops to students.<ref name=\":20\" /> Additionally, affluent families are able to afford nannies and extracurriculars that can limit the need for entertainment from screens.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/26/style/silicon-valley-nannies.html|title=Silicon Valley Nannies Are Phone Police for Kids|last=Bowles|first=Nellie|date=2018-10-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-09|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Physical health effects ==\n\n=== Adults ===\nMore screen-time has been linked with shorter sleep duration, decreased sleep efficiency, and longer sleep onset delay.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal |last1=Christensen |first1=Matthew A. |last2=Bettencourt |first2=Laura |last3=Kaye |first3=Leanne |last4=Moturu |first4=Sai T. |last5=Nguyen |first5=Kaylin T. |last6=Olgin |first6=Jeffrey E. |last7=Pletcher |first7=Mark J. |last8=Marcus |first8=Gregory M. |last9=Romigi |first9=Andrea |title=Direct Measurements of Smartphone Screen-Time: Relationships with Demographics and Sleep |journal=PLOS ONE |date=9 November 2016 |volume=11 |issue=11 |pages=e0165331 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0165331 |pmid=27829040 |pmc=5102460 |bibcode=2016PLoSO..1165331C }}</ref> When using any screen before bedtime, the blue light emitted disrupts the body\u2019s natural melatonin hormone production.<ref name=\":0\" /> Melatonin is produced by the brain\u2019s pineal gland and controls the body\u2019s internal clock.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sleep.org/articles/melatonin/|title=What Is Melatonin?|website=Sleep.org|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>  This clock is what is referred to as the body\u2019s circadian rhythm and it naturally is responsive to light.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sleep.org/articles/circadian-rhythm-body-clock/|title=What is Circadian Rhythm / Body Clock?|website=Sleep.org|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\u00a0Melatonin levels increase as the sun sets and remain at that increased state for the remainder of the night. As the sun rises, melatonin levels start to drop. This hormone reduction is what helps the body\u2019s natural rhythm wake up due to the bursts of natural sunlight.<ref name=\":12\" /> The light screens emit are in a similar spectrum of sunlight, but the blue light emission is what human circadian rhythms are most sensitive to. Studies have shown that the blue wavelengths are closely correlated to those from sunlight, which is what helps the body keep in sync with the sunrise and sunset.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/screen-time-effects-health-vision-staring-at-screens-bad-for-you-2019-1|title=What staring at a screen all day does to your brain and body|last=Wilkin|first=David Anderson, Rebecca|website=Business Insider|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> Therefore, using any screen prior to bedtime disrupts the body\u2019s production of natural bedtime hormones which can trick your brain to believe it is still daytime making it harder to fall asleep.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nMany apps promise to improve sleep by filtering out blue light produced by media devices; there have been no large studies to assess whether such apps work. Some users express dissatisfaction with the resultant orange tint of screens. Some people use blue-blocking glasses, for the purpose of attempting to block out blue light both from electronic media and from other artificial light sources.<ref>{{cite news|title=Apps Can Cut Blue Light From Devices, But Do They Help You Sleep?|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2017/11/27/561740031/apps-can-cut-blue-light-from-devices-but-do-they-help-you-sleep|accessdate=13 March 2018|work=NPR.org|date=2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs well as negatively impacting the adult sleep cycle, using screens can also affect one\u2019s physical health. Obesity is a common result of spending great amounts on screens like a television, video games, or a computer screen.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Banks |first1=Emily |last2=Jorm |first2=Louisa |last3=Rogers |first3=Kris |last4=Clements |first4=Mark |last5=Bauman |first5=Adrian |title=Screen-time, obesity, ageing and disability: findings from 91 266 participants in the 45 and Up Study |journal=Public Health Nutrition |date=22 April 2010 |volume=14 |issue=1 |pages=34\u201343 |doi=10.1017/S1368980010000674 |pmid=20409356 }}</ref> Studies have shown that if the amount of screen time adolescents spend was limited, the likelihood of obesity can be reduced.<ref name=\":14\">{{cite journal |last1=Boone |first1=Janne E |last2=Gordon-Larsen |first2=Penny |last3=Adair |first3=Linda S |last4=Popkin |first4=Barry M |title=Screen time and physical activity during adolescence: longitudinal effects on obesity in young adulthood |journal=International Journal of Behavioral Nutrition and Physical Activity |date=2007 |volume=4 |issue=1 |pages=26 |doi=10.1186/1479-5868-4-26 |pmid=17559668 |pmc=1906831 }}</ref> This sedentary behavior is largely due to the nature of most electronic activities. Sitting to watch television, playing computer games or scrolling on your phone takes time away from physical activities which leads to an increased risk of weight gain.<ref name=\":14\" />\n\n=== Children ===\nIncreased use of screens in children has led to an increase in sedentary activity because most screen usage occurs while sitting. TV and video games were once largest contributors to screen time, but the past decade has seen a shift towards smart phones and tablets.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Saunders |first1=Travis J. |last2=Vallance |first2=Jeff K. |title=Screen Time and Health Indicators Among Children and Youth: Current Evidence, Limitations and Future Directions |journal=Applied Health Economics and Health Policy |date=31 October 2016 |volume=15 |issue=3 |pages=323\u2013331 |doi=10.1007/s40258-016-0289-3 |pmid=27798796 }}</ref> It has also been found that children who watch more than 2 hours of television a day are more likely to be overweight or obese. Additionally, one study showed that the increased use of video games and other forms of media consumption led to more back pain among Norwegian teens.<ref name=\":15\">{{cite journal |last1=Rosen |first1=L.D. |last2=Lim |first2=A.F. |last3=Felt |first3=J. |last4=Carrier |first4=L.M. |last5=Cheever |first5=N.A. |last6=Lara-Ruiz |first6=J.M. |last7=Mendoza |first7=J.S. |last8=Rokkum |first8=J. |title=Media and technology use predicts ill-being among children, preteens and teenagers independent of the negative health impacts of exercise and eating habits |journal=Computers in Human Behavior |date=June 2014 |volume=35 |pages=364\u2013375 |doi=10.1016/j.chb.2014.01.036 |pmc=4338000 |pmid=25717216 }}</ref> It has been reported that screen time negatively affects health in children independently of their physical activity and eating habits.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\nOne possible explanation for the link between TV and obesity is the amount of commercials for sugary and unhealthy foods.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/obesity-prevention-source/obesity-causes/television-and-sedentary-behavior-and-obesity/|title=Television Watching and \"Sit Time\"|last=Boston|first=677 Huntington Avenue|last2=Ma 02115 +1495\u20111000|date=2012-10-21|website=Obesity Prevention Source|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> This advertising can have an effect on what gets purchased and consumed in a household. The effect of advertising was demonstrated in a study where children were shown cartoons with and without food commercials. The children who watched the food commercials along with the cartoons ate 45% more unhealthy snacks than the group who watched the cartoons without food ads.<ref name=\":16\" />\n\nIncreased use of screens in children has also been shown to have a negative impact on the sleep of children.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=https://journalistsresource.org/studies/society/public-health/screen-time-children-health-research/|title=The health effects of screen time on children: A research roundup|last=Reichel|first=Chloe|last2=May 14|first2=Journalist's Resource|date=2019-05-14|website=Journalist's Resource|access-date=2019-11-09|last3=2019}}</ref> This correlation is because much of the time spent on screens for children is at night, which can cause them to go to sleep later in addition to the blue light from the screens making it more difficult to sleep.<ref name=\":17\" /> In teens, it was found that those who had spent more time on their screens were more likely to wake in the night from notifications on their phone, or experience disruptive sleep.<ref name=\":18\">{{cite journal |last1=Foerster |first1=Milena |last2=Henneke |first2=Andrea |last3=Chetty-Mhlanga |first3=Shala |last4=R\u00f6\u00f6sli |first4=Martin |title=Impact of Adolescents' Screen Time and Nocturnal Mobile Phone-Related Awakenings on Sleep and General Health Symptoms: A Prospective Cohort Study |journal=International Journal of Environmental Research and Public Health |date=12 February 2019 |volume=16 |issue=3 |pages=518 |doi=10.3390/ijerph16030518 |pmc=6388165 |pmid=30759792 }}</ref> In adolescents, the screen content impacts sleep as well. Content that stirs emotions has been linked with a delay in the onset of sleep.<ref name=\":18\" />\n\nA 2010 review concluded that \"the use of electronic media by children and adolescents does have a negative impact on their sleep, although the precise effects and mechanisms remain unclear\", with the most consistent results associating excessive media use with shorter sleep duration and delayed bed times.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Cain |first=Neralie |last2=Gradisar |first2=Michael |title=Electronic media use and sleep in school-aged children and adolescents: a review |journal=Sleep Medicine |date=15 February 2010 |volume=11 |issue=8 |pages=735\u2013742 |url= |doi=10.1016/j.sleep.2010.02.006|pmid=20673649 }}</ref> A 2016 meta-analysis found that \"Bedtime access and use of media devices was significantly associated with inadequate sleep quantity; poor sleep quality; and excessive daytime sleepiness\".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Carter|first1=Ben|last2=Rees|first2=Philippa|last3=Hale|first3=Lauren|last4=Bhattacharjee|first4=Darsharna|last5=Paradkar|first5=Mandar S.|title=Association Between Portable Screen-Based Media Device Access or Use and Sleep Outcomes|journal=JAMA Pediatrics|date=1 December 2016|volume=170|issue=12|pages=1202\u20131208|doi=10.1001/jamapediatrics.2016.2341|pmid=27802500|pmc=5380441|url=https://kclpure.kcl.ac.uk/portal/files/60839202/poi160064.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe [[American Academy of Pediatrics]] recommends screen time for children be limited for multiple reasons, among them that \"Too much screen time can also harm the amount and quality of sleep\".<ref>{{cite web|title=American Academy of Pediatrics Announces New Recommendations for Children's Media Use|url=https://www.aap.org/en-us/about-the-aap/aap-press-room/pages/american-academy-of-pediatrics-announces-new-recommendations-for-childrens-media-use.aspx|website=www.aap.org|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref> butts are bootiful\n\n== Mental health effects ==\n\n=== Adults ===\nAs previously discussed, sleep and screen time are heavily impacted by the other and can lead to affecting one\u2019s behavior as well. If someone does not get an adequate amount of sleep, it can affect their behavior and performance for the day.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.alaskasleep.com/blog/bid/317399/why-too-much-screen-time-can-lead-to-sleep-deprivation-for-alaskans|title=Why Too Much Screen Time Can Lead to Sleep Deprivation for Alaskans|last=Hines|first=Jennifer|website=www.alaskasleep.com|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> High amounts of screen time also can significantly affect a person\u2019s mental health. With screen usage increasing as time progresses, adults have begun spending more and more time focusing their attention of screens.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencenewsforstudents.org/article/new-health-risk-too-much-screentime-sitting|title=New risk from too much screentime|last=Bates|first=Mary|date=2019-06-05|website=Science News for Students|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> This time spent sitting and viewing a screen has been linked to mental health effects such as anxiety and depression.<ref name=\":8\" /> Adults who spend six hours or greater using screen time are more likely to suffer from moderate to severe depression.<ref name=\":9\">{{cite journal |last1=Madhav |first1=K.C. |last2=Sherchand |first2=Shardulendra Prasad |last3=Sherchan |first3=Samendra |title=Association between screen time and depression among US adults |journal=Preventive Medicine Reports |date=December 2017 |volume=8 |pages=67\u201371 |doi=10.1016/j.pmedr.2017.08.005 |pmid=28879072 |pmc=5574844 }}</ref> This increased use in screen time has been shown to be directly correlated with an increased chance of depression in adults.<ref name=\":9\" /> With this added risk, lack of sleep plays a major role in a healthy mindset, but without proper rest, mental health can degrade at a higher risk.\n\n==== Brain development ====\nAn increase in screen time has been associated with negative cognitive outcomes for children between 0 and 4.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=LeBlanc |first1=Allana G. |last2=Spence |first2=John C. |last3=Carson |first3=Valerie |last4=Connor Gorber |first4=Sarah |last5=Dillman |first5=Carrie |last6=Janssen |first6=Ian |last7=Kho |first7=Michelle E. |last8=Stearns |first8=Jodie A. |last9=Timmons |first9=Brian W. |last10=Tremblay |first10=Mark S. |title=Systematic review of sedentary behaviour and health indicators in the early years (aged 0\u20134\u00a0years) |journal=Applied Physiology, Nutrition, and Metabolism |date=August 2012 |volume=37 |issue=4 |pages=753\u2013772 |doi=10.1139/h2012-063 |pmid=22765839 }}</ref> A study on Korean children aged 24\u201330 months old found that toddlers with 3 hours of TV viewing per day were three times as likely to experience a language delay.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite journal |last1=Byeon |first1=Haewon |last2=Hong |first2=Saemi |last3=Lin |first3=Haotian |title=Relationship between Television Viewing and Language Delay in Toddlers: Evidence from a Korea National Cross-Sectional Survey |journal=PLOS ONE |date=18 March 2015 |volume=10 |issue=3 |pages=e0120663 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0120663 |pmc=4365020 |pmid=25785449 |bibcode=2015PLoSO..1020663B }}</ref> Toddlers with higher TV time also scored lower on school readiness tests, which measured vocabulary, number knowledge, and classroom engagement.<ref name=\":10\" /> The same outcomes are not present in children older than 4.<ref name=\"Stiglic e023191\"/> Children who watched more TV were found to have less brain connectivity between language, visual and cognitive control regions of the brain than their peers who watched less TV.\n\nThe [[American Academy of Pediatrics]] recommend for children in age 3 - 5, a screen time not longer than 1 hour per day. According to study published in November 2019, children who have a longer screen time, have slower brain development, what hurt \"skills like imagery, mental control and self-regulation\". The scientists add that: \"This is important because the brain is developing the most rapidly in the first five years,\" \"That's when brains are very plastic and soaking up everything, forming these strong connections that last for life.\" They also stated that screens changed childhood rapidly.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nickerson |first1=Sam |title=Too Much Screen Time May Be Slowing Childhood Brain Development |url=https://www.ecowatch.com/screen-time-children-brain-development-2641261214.html |accessdate=10 November 2019 |agency=Ecowatch |date=November 8, 2019}}</ref> The over exposure also hurts skills of litteracy, cognition and language.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hutton |first1=John S. |last2=Dudley |first2=Jonathan |last3=Horowitz-Kraus |first3=Tzipi |last4=DeWitt |first4=Tom |last5=Holland |first5=Scott K. |title=Associations Between Screen-Based Media Use and Brain White Matter Integrity in Preschool-Aged Children |journal=JAMA Pediatrics |date=4 November 2019 |pages=e193869 |doi=10.1001/jamapediatrics.2019.3869 |pmid=31682712 }}</ref>\n\n==== Behavioral impact ====\nScreen use has been implicated with a slew of behavioral effects, especially in children. The primary effect is an increase in sedentary activity. Approximately 47% of American children spend 2 or more hours per day on screen-based sedentary activities.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sisson |first1=Susan B. |last2=Church |first2=Timothy S. |last3=Martin |first3=Corby K. |last4=Tudor-Locke |first4=Catrine |last5=Smith |first5=Steven R. |last6=Bouchard |first6=Claude |last7=Earnest |first7=Conrad P. |last8=Rankinen |first8=Tuomo |last9=Newton |first9=Robert L. |last10=Katzmarzyk |first10=Peter T. |title=Profiles of sedentary behavior in children and adolescents: The US National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey, 2001\u20132006 |journal=International Journal of Pediatric Obesity |date=January 2009 |volume=4 |issue=4 |pages=353\u2013359 |doi=10.3109/17477160902934777 |pmid=19922052 |pmc=2891818 }}</ref> This is in contrast with the 25.5% who reported at least 20 minutes of physical per day for a week.<ref name=\":11\">{{cite journal |last1=Sisson |first1=Susan B. |last2=Broyles |first2=Stephanie T. |last3=Baker |first3=Birgitta L. |last4=Katzmarzyk |first4=Peter T. |title=Screen Time, Physical Activity, and Overweight in U.S. Youth: National Survey of Children's Health 2003 |journal=Journal of Adolescent Health |date=September 2010 |volume=47 |issue=3 |pages=309\u2013311 |doi=10.1016/j.jadohealth.2010.02.016 |pmid=20708572 }}</ref> Additionally, the likelihood of a child participating in physical activity has been shown to decrease with increasing screen use.<ref name=\":11\" /> Screen use can also affect interpersonal skills. UCLA researchers reported that sixth-graders who went five days without screen use were significantly better at reading human emotions than sixth-graders with average screen use.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newsroom.ucla.edu/releases/in-our-digital-world-are-young-people-losing-the-ability-to-read-emotions|title=In our digital world, are young people losing the ability to read emotions?|website=UCLA|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n\n==== Academic performance ====\nAcademic performance can be improved by screen time depending on the length and content of exposure. Toddlers after the age of 18 months can be exposed to high-quality programming such as Sesame Street or PBS that provide educational television.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.aap.org/en-us/about-the-aap/aap-press-room/Pages/American-Academy-of-Pediatrics-Announces-New-Recommendations-for-Childrens-Media-Use.aspx|title=American Academy of Pediatrics Announces New Recommendations for Children's Media Use|website=AAP.org|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> The right content can prove beneficial, but too much screen time distracts students from studying.<ref name=\":3\" /> It is important for parents to establish a limit to how much screen time their children can use per day. Limiting and monitoring children's screen usage can increase cognitive development, but further research is required to get a better understanding of how screen time positively affects academic performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.healio.com/pediatrics/school-health/news/online/%7Bf0d24d3f-fe0e-40ec-adf6-b68f6a51102f%7D/not-all-screen-time-negatively-affects-kids-academic-achievement|title=Not all screen time negatively affects kids' academic achievement|last=M|first=Adelantado-Renau|last2=J|first2=et al JAMA Pediatr 2019;doi:10 1001/jamapediatrics 2019 3176 Whitlock|website=www.healio.com|access-date=2019-11-09|last3=September 26|first3=Masur PK JAMA Pediatr 2019;doi:10 1001/jamapediatrics 2019 3191|last4=2019}}</ref> On the other hand, increased screen use has been associated with missing school assignments.<ref name=\":8\" /> Students who used screens for more than two hours a day are twice as likely to not turn in homework on a regular basis.<ref name=\":8\" /> It is yet to be proven that screen time can significantly enhance academic performance, but it is known that increased use in screen time distracts students from focusing on class assignments.[[File:Kindergarten iPad.jpg|thumb|A child using a tablet]]\n\n== Limitations on screen time ==\n\n=== Adults ===\nThere is no consensus on the safe amount of screen time for adults. Ideally, adults should limit their screen time similar to children and only use screens for about two hours a day.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scripps.org/news_items/6626-how-much-screen-time-is-too-much|title=How Much Screen Time is Too Much?|last=February 22|last2=2019|date=2019-02-08|website=Scripps Health|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> However, many adults spend up to 11 hours a day looking at a screen. Adults many times work jobs that require viewing screens which leads to the high screen time usage.<ref name=\":4\" /> Adults obligated to view screens for a means of work may not be able to use screen time less than two hours, but there are other recommendations that help mitigate negative health effects. For example, breaking up continuous blocks of screen time usage by stretching, maintaining good posture, and intermittently focusing on a distant object for 20 seconds.<ref name=\":4\" /> Furthermore, to mitigate the behavioral effects, adults are encouraged not to eat in front of a screen to avoid habit formation and to keep track of their screen use every day.<ref name=\":4\" /> Specialists also recommend that adults analyze their daily screen time usage and replace some of the unnecessary usage with a physical activity or social event.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Children ===\nScreen time has been shown to affect children more than adults. Extensive screen time can have a lasting effect on children whose brains and bodies are still developing.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cheung |first1=Celeste H. M. |last2=Bedford |first2=Rachael |last3=Saez De Urabain |first3=Irati R. |last4=Karmiloff-Smith |first4=Annette |last5=Smith |first5=Tim J. |title=Daily touchscreen use in infants and toddlers is associated with reduced sleep and delayed sleep onset |journal=Scientific Reports |date=13 April 2017 |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=46104 |doi=10.1038/srep46104 |pmid=28406474 |pmc=5390665 |bibcode=2017NatSR...746104C }}</ref> The American Academy of Pediatrics breaks down limitations for children by age. They suggest that infants younger than 18 months should not be exposed to any screens (apart from video chats).<ref name=\":4\" /> Kids around 18\u201324 months old should furthermore be limited to high-quality media sources and supervised by adults while doing so. Once kids reach ages 2\u20135, the amount of screen time increases to up to an hour a day on any device total.<ref name=\":4\" /> There is no formal recommendation beyond the age of 5. The American Academy of Pediatrics emphasizes the role of parents in controlling screen time after the age of 5.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAn ongoing study reported from the National Institutes of Health concluded that preteens who spent over 7 hours on screens a day and children who spend less than 7 hours a day had noticeably different development of their cerebral cortex. This part of the brain usually thins as people mature but the accelerated decrease could potentially be linked to amounts spent on screens.<ref name=\":4\" /> Long-lasting effects like this should be considered when trying to implement limitations for children. Parents should be involved in monitoring their child\u2019s screen usage and try to implement better and healthier practices by encouraging better bedtime routines, educating youth about the lasting effects, and limiting the number of available screens in the environment.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=LeBourgeois |first1=Monique K. |last2=Hale |first2=Lauren |last3=Chang |first3=Anne-Marie |last4=Akacem |first4=Lameese D. |last5=Montgomery-Downs |first5=Hawley E. |last6=Buxton |first6=Orfeu M. |title=Digital Media and Sleep in Childhood and Adolescence |journal=Pediatrics |date=1 November 2017 |volume=140 |issue=Supplement 2 |pages=S92\u2013S96 |doi=10.1542/peds.2016-1758J |pmid=29093040 |pmc=5658795 }}</ref>\n\n=== Legal ===\nSome countries have begun implementing regulations on-screen time to protect their citizens. In Taiwan, there is a legal time limit on how much screen time kids can participate in. If the excessive screen use is found to have negatively affected a child's health, parents can be fined up to $1595.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/3682621/this-country-just-made-it-illegal-to-give-kids-too-much-screen-time/|title=This Place Just Made it Illegal to Give Kids Too Much Screen Time|website=Time|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> The new ban establishes time spent on screens as detrimental to health, and uses similar language to smoking and drinking regulations.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nOther Asian countries have passed similar laws. In Korea, video game use among students has been implicated in many psychological and physical issues, like high rates of depression.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/south-korea-introduces-yet-another-law-curb-gamings-ills-flna158168|title=South Korea introduces yet another law to curb gaming's ills|website=NBC News|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> Korea has established the Cool Down Program that makes video games automatically shut down after 2 hours of play, and can only be rebooted after 10 minutes of downtime.<ref name=\":6\" /> This is the second law enacted in Korea to limit gaming for students. The other law is called the \u201cShut Down Law\u201d that bans gaming for children under the age of 16 between midnight and 6 am.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nChina has enacted similar restrictions for users of the video game Honour of Kings. It had been regularly condemned by the government because of its addictive nature which is compounded by accessibility through a mobile app.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-45432863|title=State data to limit China child gamers|date=2018-09-06|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> To regulate the game, the government makes users create an account, which includes their age. Users under the age of 13 can only play for 1 hour per day, and those between the ages of 13 and 17 are limited to two hours per day.<ref name=\":7\" /> These policies attempt to limit screen time for children in response to research that reveals negative impacts of screens on children.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dark therapy]]\n* [[Delayed sleep phase disorder]]\n* [[f.lux]]\n* [[Light effects on circadian rhythm]]\n* [[Night Shift (software)]]\n* [[Red Moon (software)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Digital media use and mental health}}\n\n[[Category:Digital media use and mental health]]\n[[Category:Lifestyles]]\n[[Category:Obesity]]\n[[Category:Medical terminology]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses|Screen time (disambiguation)}}\n{{See also|Digital media use and mental health|Gaming disorder|Mobile phone overuse}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n\n'''Screen time''' is the amount of time spent using a device with a [[Display device|screen]] such as a [[smartphone]], computer, television, or [[video game console]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/screen+time|title=Definition of SCREEN TIME|website=www.merriam-webster.com|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> The concept is under significant research with related concepts in [[digital media use and mental health]]. Studies show that screen time directly impacts child development, and mental and physical health.<ref name=\"Stiglic e023191\">{{cite journal |last1=Stiglic |first1=Neza |last2=Viner |first2=Russell M |title=Effects of screentime on the health and well-being of children and adolescents: a systematic review of reviews |journal=BMJ Open |date=3 January 2019 |volume=9 |issue=1 |pages=e023191 |doi=10.1136/bmjopen-2018-023191 |pmid=30606703 |pmc=6326346 }}</ref> The positive or negative health effects or screen time are influenced by levels and content of exposure. To prevent harmful exposure to screen time, some governments have placed regulations on its usage.<ref name=\":5\" /> \n[[File:Screen time.jpg|thumb|People using phones whilst walking]]\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Statistics ===\nThe first electronic screen was the cathode ray tube (CRT), which was invented in 1897 and commercialized in 1922.<ref name=\":1\">{{cite journal |title=The Cathode Ray Tube and its Applications |journal=Nature |date=July 1942 |volume=150 |issue=3794 |pages=74 |doi=10.1038/150074d0 |bibcode=1942Natur.150S..74. }}</ref> CRT\u2019s were the most popular choice for display screens until the rise of liquid crystal displays (LCDs) in the early 2000s.<ref name=\":1\" /> Screens are now an essential part of entertainment, advertising, and information technologies.\n\nSince their popularization in 2007, smartphones have become ubiquitous in daily life. In 2015, 64% of all American adults reported owning a smartphone, including 85% of individuals between 18 and 29 years old.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pewresearch.org/internet/2015/04/01/us-smartphone-use-in-2015/|title=U.S. Smartphone Use in 2015|last=NW|first=1615 L. St|last2=Suite 800Washington|date=2015-04-01|website=Pew Research Center: Internet, Science & Tech|access-date=2019-11-09|last3=Inquiries|first3=DC 20036USA202-419-4300 {{!}} Main202-857-8562 {{!}} Fax202-419-4372 {{!}} Media}}</ref> An American survey found a median of 3.7 minutes per hour of screen time over a 30 day period.<ref name=\":2\" /> \n\nAll forms of screens are most frequently used by younger age brackets, particularly young children. 98.5% of surveyed children aged 12\u201315 reported daily TV use and 91.1% reported daily computer use over a period of 30 days.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo68061|title=TV watching and computer use in U.S. youth aged 12-15, 2012|last=Herrick|first=Kirsten A|last2=Fakhouri|first2=Tala H. I|last3=Carlson|first3=Susan A|last4=Fulton|first4=Janet E|last5=National Center for Health Statistics (U.S.)|date=2014|language=English|oclc=897600869}}</ref>\n\n=== Race, socioeconomic class, and screen time ===\nResearch has shown that race and socioeconomic class are associated with overall screen time. Younger demographics and individuals who self-identified as Black and \"Other\" were associated with above average screen use.<ref name=\":2\" /> Additionally, Black and Latino Americans had longer screen times because of less access to desktop computers, which thus leads to more time on phones.<ref name=\":2\" /> In children, the divide is much larger. One average white children spend 8.5 hours a day with digital media, and Black and Latino children spend about 13 hours a day on screens.<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://dcmp.org/learn/301-children-media-and-race-media-use-among-white-black-hispanic-and-asian-american-children|title=Children, Media, and Race: Media Use Among White, Black, Hispanic, and Asian American Children|website=dcmp.org|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\u00a0Black and Latino children are also more likely to have TVs in their rooms, which contributes to their increased use of screen time.<ref name=\":19\" />\n\nThe discrepancy in the amount of screen time can also be attributed to a difference in income.\u00a0 In more affluent private schools, there has been a larger push to remove screens from education in order to limit the negative impacts that have been found from screen time.<ref name=\":20\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/26/style/digital-divide-screens-schools.html|title=The Digital Gap Between Rich and Poor Kids Is Not What We Expected|last=Bowles|first=Nellie|date=2018-10-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-09|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> However, in public schools there is more push for the use of technology with some public schools advertising free iPads and laptops to students.<ref name=\":20\" /> Additionally, affluent families are able to afford nannies and extracurriculars that can limit the need for entertainment from screens.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/10/26/style/silicon-valley-nannies.html|title=Silicon Valley Nannies Are Phone Police for Kids|last=Bowles|first=Nellie|date=2018-10-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-09|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n== Physical health effects ==\n\n=== Adults ===\nMore screen-time has been linked with shorter sleep duration, decreased sleep efficiency, and longer sleep onset delay.<ref name=\":2\">{{cite journal |last1=Christensen |first1=Matthew A. |last2=Bettencourt |first2=Laura |last3=Kaye |first3=Leanne |last4=Moturu |first4=Sai T. |last5=Nguyen |first5=Kaylin T. |last6=Olgin |first6=Jeffrey E. |last7=Pletcher |first7=Mark J. |last8=Marcus |first8=Gregory M. |last9=Romigi |first9=Andrea |title=Direct Measurements of Smartphone Screen-Time: Relationships with Demographics and Sleep |journal=PLOS ONE |date=9 November 2016 |volume=11 |issue=11 |pages=e0165331 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0165331 |pmid=27829040 |pmc=5102460 |bibcode=2016PLoSO..1165331C }}</ref> When using any screen before bedtime, the blue light emitted disrupts the body\u2019s natural melatonin hormone production.<ref name=\":0\" /> Melatonin is produced by the brain\u2019s pineal gland and controls the body\u2019s internal clock.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sleep.org/articles/melatonin/|title=What Is Melatonin?|website=Sleep.org|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>  This clock is what is referred to as the body\u2019s circadian rhythm and it naturally is responsive to light.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sleep.org/articles/circadian-rhythm-body-clock/|title=What is Circadian Rhythm / Body Clock?|website=Sleep.org|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\u00a0Melatonin levels increase as the sun sets and remain at that increased state for the remainder of the night. As the sun rises, melatonin levels start to drop. This hormone reduction is what helps the body\u2019s natural rhythm wake up due to the bursts of natural sunlight.<ref name=\":12\" /> The light screens emit are in a similar spectrum of sunlight, but the blue light emission is what human circadian rhythms are most sensitive to. Studies have shown that the blue wavelengths are closely correlated to those from sunlight, which is what helps the body keep in sync with the sunrise and sunset.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/screen-time-effects-health-vision-staring-at-screens-bad-for-you-2019-1|title=What staring at a screen all day does to your brain and body|last=Wilkin|first=David Anderson, Rebecca|website=Business Insider|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> Therefore, using any screen prior to bedtime disrupts the body\u2019s production of natural bedtime hormones which can trick your brain to believe it is still daytime making it harder to fall asleep.<ref name=\":13\" />\n\nMany apps promise to improve sleep by filtering out blue light produced by media devices; there have been no large studies to assess whether such apps work. Some users express dissatisfaction with the resultant orange tint of screens. Some people use blue-blocking glasses, for the purpose of attempting to block out blue light both from electronic media and from other artificial light sources.<ref>{{cite news|title=Apps Can Cut Blue Light From Devices, But Do They Help You Sleep?|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2017/11/27/561740031/apps-can-cut-blue-light-from-devices-but-do-they-help-you-sleep|accessdate=13 March 2018|work=NPR.org|date=2017|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAs well as negatively impacting the adult sleep cycle, using screens can also affect one\u2019s physical health. Obesity is a common result of spending great amounts on screens like a television, video games, or a computer screen.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Banks |first1=Emily |last2=Jorm |first2=Louisa |last3=Rogers |first3=Kris |last4=Clements |first4=Mark |last5=Bauman |first5=Adrian |title=Screen-time, obesity, ageing and disability: findings from 91 266 participants in the 45 and Up Study |journal=Public Health Nutrition |date=22 April 2010 |volume=14 |issue=1 |pages=34\u201343 |doi=10.1017/S1368980010000674 |pmid=20409356 }}</ref> Studies have shown that if the amount of screen time adolescents spend was limited, the likelihood of obesity can be reduced.<ref name=\":14\">{{cite journal |last1=Boone |first1=Janne E |last2=Gordon-Larsen |first2=Penny |last3=Adair |first3=Linda S |last4=Popkin |first4=Barry M |title=Screen time and physical activity during adolescence: longitudinal effects on obesity in young adulthood |journal=International Journal of Behavioral Nutrition and Physical Activity |date=2007 |volume=4 |issue=1 |pages=26 |doi=10.1186/1479-5868-4-26 |pmid=17559668 |pmc=1906831 }}</ref> This sedentary behavior is largely due to the nature of most electronic activities. Sitting to watch television, playing computer games or scrolling on your phone takes time away from physical activities which leads to an increased risk of weight gain.<ref name=\":14\" />\n\n=== Children ===\nIncreased use of screens in children has led to an increase in sedentary activity because most screen usage occurs while sitting. TV and video games were once largest contributors to screen time, but the past decade has seen a shift towards smart phones and tablets.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Saunders |first1=Travis J. |last2=Vallance |first2=Jeff K. |title=Screen Time and Health Indicators Among Children and Youth: Current Evidence, Limitations and Future Directions |journal=Applied Health Economics and Health Policy |date=31 October 2016 |volume=15 |issue=3 |pages=323\u2013331 |doi=10.1007/s40258-016-0289-3 |pmid=27798796 }}</ref> It has also been found that children who watch more than 2 hours of television a day are more likely to be overweight or obese. Additionally, one study showed that the increased use of video games and other forms of media consumption led to more back pain among Norwegian teens.<ref name=\":15\">{{cite journal |last1=Rosen |first1=L.D. |last2=Lim |first2=A.F. |last3=Felt |first3=J. |last4=Carrier |first4=L.M. |last5=Cheever |first5=N.A. |last6=Lara-Ruiz |first6=J.M. |last7=Mendoza |first7=J.S. |last8=Rokkum |first8=J. |title=Media and technology use predicts ill-being among children, preteens and teenagers independent of the negative health impacts of exercise and eating habits |journal=Computers in Human Behavior |date=June 2014 |volume=35 |pages=364\u2013375 |doi=10.1016/j.chb.2014.01.036 |pmc=4338000 |pmid=25717216 }}</ref> It has been reported that screen time negatively affects health in children independently of their physical activity and eating habits.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\nOne possible explanation for the link between TV and obesity is the amount of commercials for sugary and unhealthy foods.<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.hsph.harvard.edu/obesity-prevention-source/obesity-causes/television-and-sedentary-behavior-and-obesity/|title=Television Watching and \"Sit Time\"|last=Boston|first=677 Huntington Avenue|last2=Ma 02115 +1495\u20111000|date=2012-10-21|website=Obesity Prevention Source|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> This advertising can have an effect on what gets purchased and consumed in a household. The effect of advertising was demonstrated in a study where children were shown cartoons with and without food commercials. The children who watched the food commercials along with the cartoons ate 45% more unhealthy snacks than the group who watched the cartoons without food ads.<ref name=\":16\" />\n\nIncreased use of screens in children has also been shown to have a negative impact on the sleep of children.<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=https://journalistsresource.org/studies/society/public-health/screen-time-children-health-research/|title=The health effects of screen time on children: A research roundup|last=Reichel|first=Chloe|last2=May 14|first2=Journalist's Resource|date=2019-05-14|website=Journalist's Resource|access-date=2019-11-09|last3=2019}}</ref> This correlation is because much of the time spent on screens for children is at night, which can cause them to go to sleep later in addition to the blue light from the screens making it more difficult to sleep.<ref name=\":17\" /> In teens, it was found that those who had spent more time on their screens were more likely to wake in the night from notifications on their phone, or experience disruptive sleep.<ref name=\":18\">{{cite journal |last1=Foerster |first1=Milena |last2=Henneke |first2=Andrea |last3=Chetty-Mhlanga |first3=Shala |last4=R\u00f6\u00f6sli |first4=Martin |title=Impact of Adolescents' Screen Time and Nocturnal Mobile Phone-Related Awakenings on Sleep and General Health Symptoms: A Prospective Cohort Study |journal=International Journal of Environmental Research and Public Health |date=12 February 2019 |volume=16 |issue=3 |pages=518 |doi=10.3390/ijerph16030518 |pmc=6388165 |pmid=30759792 }}</ref> In adolescents, the screen content impacts sleep as well. Content that stirs emotions has been linked with a delay in the onset of sleep.<ref name=\":18\" />\n\nA 2010 review concluded that \"the use of electronic media by children and adolescents does have a negative impact on their sleep, although the precise effects and mechanisms remain unclear\", with the most consistent results associating excessive media use with shorter sleep duration and delayed bed times.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Cain |first=Neralie |last2=Gradisar |first2=Michael |title=Electronic media use and sleep in school-aged children and adolescents: a review |journal=Sleep Medicine |date=15 February 2010 |volume=11 |issue=8 |pages=735\u2013742 |url= |doi=10.1016/j.sleep.2010.02.006|pmid=20673649 }}</ref> A 2016 meta-analysis found that \"Bedtime access and use of media devices was significantly associated with inadequate sleep quantity; poor sleep quality; and excessive daytime sleepiness\".<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Carter|first1=Ben|last2=Rees|first2=Philippa|last3=Hale|first3=Lauren|last4=Bhattacharjee|first4=Darsharna|last5=Paradkar|first5=Mandar S.|title=Association Between Portable Screen-Based Media Device Access or Use and Sleep Outcomes|journal=JAMA Pediatrics|date=1 December 2016|volume=170|issue=12|pages=1202\u20131208|doi=10.1001/jamapediatrics.2016.2341|pmid=27802500|pmc=5380441|url=https://kclpure.kcl.ac.uk/portal/files/60839202/poi160064.pdf}}</ref>\n\nThe [[American Academy of Pediatrics]] recommends screen time for children be limited for multiple reasons, among them that \"Too much screen time can also harm the amount and quality of sleep\".<ref>{{cite web|title=American Academy of Pediatrics Announces New Recommendations for Children's Media Use|url=https://www.aap.org/en-us/about-the-aap/aap-press-room/pages/american-academy-of-pediatrics-announces-new-recommendations-for-childrens-media-use.aspx|website=www.aap.org|accessdate=13 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Mental health effects ==\n\n=== Adults ===\nAs previously discussed, sleep and screen time are heavily impacted by the other and can lead to affecting one\u2019s behavior as well. If someone does not get an adequate amount of sleep, it can affect their behavior and performance for the day.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.alaskasleep.com/blog/bid/317399/why-too-much-screen-time-can-lead-to-sleep-deprivation-for-alaskans|title=Why Too Much Screen Time Can Lead to Sleep Deprivation for Alaskans|last=Hines|first=Jennifer|website=www.alaskasleep.com|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> High amounts of screen time also can significantly affect a person\u2019s mental health. With screen usage increasing as time progresses, adults have begun spending more and more time focusing their attention of screens.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.sciencenewsforstudents.org/article/new-health-risk-too-much-screentime-sitting|title=New risk from too much screentime|last=Bates|first=Mary|date=2019-06-05|website=Science News for Students|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> This time spent sitting and viewing a screen has been linked to mental health effects such as anxiety and depression.<ref name=\":8\" /> Adults who spend six hours or greater using screen time are more likely to suffer from moderate to severe depression.<ref name=\":9\">{{cite journal |last1=Madhav |first1=K.C. |last2=Sherchand |first2=Shardulendra Prasad |last3=Sherchan |first3=Samendra |title=Association between screen time and depression among US adults |journal=Preventive Medicine Reports |date=December 2017 |volume=8 |pages=67\u201371 |doi=10.1016/j.pmedr.2017.08.005 |pmid=28879072 |pmc=5574844 }}</ref> This increased use in screen time has been shown to be directly correlated with an increased chance of depression in adults.<ref name=\":9\" /> With this added risk, lack of sleep plays a major role in a healthy mindset, but without proper rest, mental health can degrade at a higher risk.\n\n==== Brain development ====\nAn increase in screen time has been associated with negative cognitive outcomes for children between 0 and 4.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=LeBlanc |first1=Allana G. |last2=Spence |first2=John C. |last3=Carson |first3=Valerie |last4=Connor Gorber |first4=Sarah |last5=Dillman |first5=Carrie |last6=Janssen |first6=Ian |last7=Kho |first7=Michelle E. |last8=Stearns |first8=Jodie A. |last9=Timmons |first9=Brian W. |last10=Tremblay |first10=Mark S. |title=Systematic review of sedentary behaviour and health indicators in the early years (aged 0\u20134\u00a0years) |journal=Applied Physiology, Nutrition, and Metabolism |date=August 2012 |volume=37 |issue=4 |pages=753\u2013772 |doi=10.1139/h2012-063 |pmid=22765839 }}</ref> A study on Korean children aged 24\u201330 months old found that toddlers with 3 hours of TV viewing per day were three times as likely to experience a language delay.<ref name=\":10\">{{cite journal |last1=Byeon |first1=Haewon |last2=Hong |first2=Saemi |last3=Lin |first3=Haotian |title=Relationship between Television Viewing and Language Delay in Toddlers: Evidence from a Korea National Cross-Sectional Survey |journal=PLOS ONE |date=18 March 2015 |volume=10 |issue=3 |pages=e0120663 |doi=10.1371/journal.pone.0120663 |pmc=4365020 |pmid=25785449 |bibcode=2015PLoSO..1020663B }}</ref> Toddlers with higher TV time also scored lower on school readiness tests, which measured vocabulary, number knowledge, and classroom engagement.<ref name=\":10\" /> The same outcomes are not present in children older than 4.<ref name=\"Stiglic e023191\"/> Children who watched more TV were found to have less brain connectivity between language, visual and cognitive control regions of the brain than their peers who watched less TV.\n\nThe [[American Academy of Pediatrics]] recommend for children in age 3 - 5, a screen time not longer than 1 hour per day. According to study published in November 2019, children who have a longer screen time, have slower brain development, what hurt \"skills like imagery, mental control and self-regulation\". The scientists add that: \"This is important because the brain is developing the most rapidly in the first five years,\" \"That's when brains are very plastic and soaking up everything, forming these strong connections that last for life.\" They also stated that screens changed childhood rapidly.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Nickerson |first1=Sam |title=Too Much Screen Time May Be Slowing Childhood Brain Development |url=https://www.ecowatch.com/screen-time-children-brain-development-2641261214.html |accessdate=10 November 2019 |agency=Ecowatch |date=November 8, 2019}}</ref> The over exposure also hurts skills of litteracy, cognition and language.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Hutton |first1=John S. |last2=Dudley |first2=Jonathan |last3=Horowitz-Kraus |first3=Tzipi |last4=DeWitt |first4=Tom |last5=Holland |first5=Scott K. |title=Associations Between Screen-Based Media Use and Brain White Matter Integrity in Preschool-Aged Children |journal=JAMA Pediatrics |date=4 November 2019 |pages=e193869 |doi=10.1001/jamapediatrics.2019.3869 |pmid=31682712 }}</ref>\n\n==== Behavioral impact ====\nScreen use has been implicated with a slew of behavioral effects, especially in children. The primary effect is an increase in sedentary activity. Approximately 47% of American children spend 2 or more hours per day on screen-based sedentary activities.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Sisson |first1=Susan B. |last2=Church |first2=Timothy S. |last3=Martin |first3=Corby K. |last4=Tudor-Locke |first4=Catrine |last5=Smith |first5=Steven R. |last6=Bouchard |first6=Claude |last7=Earnest |first7=Conrad P. |last8=Rankinen |first8=Tuomo |last9=Newton |first9=Robert L. |last10=Katzmarzyk |first10=Peter T. |title=Profiles of sedentary behavior in children and adolescents: The US National Health and Nutrition Examination Survey, 2001\u20132006 |journal=International Journal of Pediatric Obesity |date=January 2009 |volume=4 |issue=4 |pages=353\u2013359 |doi=10.3109/17477160902934777 |pmid=19922052 |pmc=2891818 }}</ref> This is in contrast with the 25.5% who reported at least 20 minutes of physical per day for a week.<ref name=\":11\">{{cite journal |last1=Sisson |first1=Susan B. |last2=Broyles |first2=Stephanie T. |last3=Baker |first3=Birgitta L. |last4=Katzmarzyk |first4=Peter T. |title=Screen Time, Physical Activity, and Overweight in U.S. Youth: National Survey of Children's Health 2003 |journal=Journal of Adolescent Health |date=September 2010 |volume=47 |issue=3 |pages=309\u2013311 |doi=10.1016/j.jadohealth.2010.02.016 |pmid=20708572 }}</ref> Additionally, the likelihood of a child participating in physical activity has been shown to decrease with increasing screen use.<ref name=\":11\" /> Screen use can also affect interpersonal skills. UCLA researchers reported that sixth-graders who went five days without screen use were significantly better at reading human emotions than sixth-graders with average screen use.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://newsroom.ucla.edu/releases/in-our-digital-world-are-young-people-losing-the-ability-to-read-emotions|title=In our digital world, are young people losing the ability to read emotions?|website=UCLA|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n\n==== Academic performance ====\nAcademic performance can be improved by screen time depending on the length and content of exposure. Toddlers after the age of 18 months can be exposed to high-quality programming such as Sesame Street or PBS that provide educational television.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.aap.org/en-us/about-the-aap/aap-press-room/Pages/American-Academy-of-Pediatrics-Announces-New-Recommendations-for-Childrens-Media-Use.aspx|title=American Academy of Pediatrics Announces New Recommendations for Children's Media Use|website=AAP.org|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> The right content can prove beneficial, but too much screen time distracts students from studying.<ref name=\":3\" /> It is important for parents to establish a limit to how much screen time their children can use per day. Limiting and monitoring children's screen usage can increase cognitive development, but further research is required to get a better understanding of how screen time positively affects academic performance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.healio.com/pediatrics/school-health/news/online/%7Bf0d24d3f-fe0e-40ec-adf6-b68f6a51102f%7D/not-all-screen-time-negatively-affects-kids-academic-achievement|title=Not all screen time negatively affects kids' academic achievement|last=M|first=Adelantado-Renau|last2=J|first2=et al JAMA Pediatr 2019;doi:10 1001/jamapediatrics 2019 3176 Whitlock|website=www.healio.com|access-date=2019-11-09|last3=September 26|first3=Masur PK JAMA Pediatr 2019;doi:10 1001/jamapediatrics 2019 3191|last4=2019}}</ref> On the other hand, increased screen use has been associated with missing school assignments.<ref name=\":8\" /> Students who used screens for more than two hours a day are twice as likely to not turn in homework on a regular basis.<ref name=\":8\" /> It is yet to be proven that screen time can significantly enhance academic performance, but it is known that increased use in screen time distracts students from focusing on class assignments.[[File:Kindergarten iPad.jpg|thumb|A child using a tablet]]\n\n== Limitations on screen time ==\n\n=== Adults ===\nThere is no consensus on the safe amount of screen time for adults. Ideally, adults should limit their screen time similar to children and only use screens for about two hours a day.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.scripps.org/news_items/6626-how-much-screen-time-is-too-much|title=How Much Screen Time is Too Much?|last=February 22|last2=2019|date=2019-02-08|website=Scripps Health|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> However, many adults spend up to 11 hours a day looking at a screen. Adults many times work jobs that require viewing screens which leads to the high screen time usage.<ref name=\":4\" /> Adults obligated to view screens for a means of work may not be able to use screen time less than two hours, but there are other recommendations that help mitigate negative health effects. For example, breaking up continuous blocks of screen time usage by stretching, maintaining good posture, and intermittently focusing on a distant object for 20 seconds.<ref name=\":4\" /> Furthermore, to mitigate the behavioral effects, adults are encouraged not to eat in front of a screen to avoid habit formation and to keep track of their screen use every day.<ref name=\":4\" /> Specialists also recommend that adults analyze their daily screen time usage and replace some of the unnecessary usage with a physical activity or social event.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n=== Children ===\nScreen time has been shown to affect children more than adults. Extensive screen time can have a lasting effect on children whose brains and bodies are still developing.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Cheung |first1=Celeste H. M. |last2=Bedford |first2=Rachael |last3=Saez De Urabain |first3=Irati R. |last4=Karmiloff-Smith |first4=Annette |last5=Smith |first5=Tim J. |title=Daily touchscreen use in infants and toddlers is associated with reduced sleep and delayed sleep onset |journal=Scientific Reports |date=13 April 2017 |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=46104 |doi=10.1038/srep46104 |pmid=28406474 |pmc=5390665 |bibcode=2017NatSR...746104C }}</ref> The American Academy of Pediatrics breaks down limitations for children by age. They suggest that infants younger than 18 months should not be exposed to any screens (apart from video chats).<ref name=\":4\" /> Kids around 18\u201324 months old should furthermore be limited to high-quality media sources and supervised by adults while doing so. Once kids reach ages 2\u20135, the amount of screen time increases to up to an hour a day on any device total.<ref name=\":4\" /> There is no formal recommendation beyond the age of 5. The American Academy of Pediatrics emphasizes the role of parents in controlling screen time after the age of 5.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAn ongoing study reported from the National Institutes of Health concluded that preteens who spent over 7 hours on screens a day and children who spend less than 7 hours a day had noticeably different development of their cerebral cortex. This part of the brain usually thins as people mature but the accelerated decrease could potentially be linked to amounts spent on screens.<ref name=\":4\" /> Long-lasting effects like this should be considered when trying to implement limitations for children. Parents should be involved in monitoring their child\u2019s screen usage and try to implement better and healthier practices by encouraging better bedtime routines, educating youth about the lasting effects, and limiting the number of available screens in the environment.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=LeBourgeois |first1=Monique K. |last2=Hale |first2=Lauren |last3=Chang |first3=Anne-Marie |last4=Akacem |first4=Lameese D. |last5=Montgomery-Downs |first5=Hawley E. |last6=Buxton |first6=Orfeu M. |title=Digital Media and Sleep in Childhood and Adolescence |journal=Pediatrics |date=1 November 2017 |volume=140 |issue=Supplement 2 |pages=S92\u2013S96 |doi=10.1542/peds.2016-1758J |pmid=29093040 |pmc=5658795 }}</ref>\n\n=== Legal ===\nSome countries have begun implementing regulations on-screen time to protect their citizens. In Taiwan, there is a legal time limit on how much screen time kids can participate in. If the excessive screen use is found to have negatively affected a child's health, parents can be fined up to $1595.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/3682621/this-country-just-made-it-illegal-to-give-kids-too-much-screen-time/|title=This Place Just Made it Illegal to Give Kids Too Much Screen Time|website=Time|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> The new ban establishes time spent on screens as detrimental to health, and uses similar language to smoking and drinking regulations.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nOther Asian countries have passed similar laws. In Korea, video game use among students has been implicated in many psychological and physical issues, like high rates of depression.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/tech/tech-news/south-korea-introduces-yet-another-law-curb-gamings-ills-flna158168|title=South Korea introduces yet another law to curb gaming's ills|website=NBC News|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> Korea has established the Cool Down Program that makes video games automatically shut down after 2 hours of play, and can only be rebooted after 10 minutes of downtime.<ref name=\":6\" /> This is the second law enacted in Korea to limit gaming for students. The other law is called the \u201cShut Down Law\u201d that bans gaming for children under the age of 16 between midnight and 6 am.<ref name=\":6\" />\n\nChina has enacted similar restrictions for users of the video game Honour of Kings. It had been regularly condemned by the government because of its addictive nature which is compounded by accessibility through a mobile app.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/technology-45432863|title=State data to limit China child gamers|date=2018-09-06|access-date=2019-11-08}}</ref> To regulate the game, the government makes users create an account, which includes their age. Users under the age of 13 can only play for 1 hour per day, and those between the ages of 13 and 17 are limited to two hours per day.<ref name=\":7\" /> These policies attempt to limit screen time for children in response to research that reveals negative impacts of screens on children.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Dark therapy]]\n* [[Delayed sleep phase disorder]]\n* [[f.lux]]\n* [[Light effects on circadian rhythm]]\n* [[Night Shift (software)]]\n* [[Red Moon (software)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Digital media use and mental health}}\n\n[[Category:Digital media use and mental health]]\n[[Category:Lifestyles]]\n[[Category:Obesity]]\n[[Category:Medical terminology]]\n", "name_user": "2607:fea8:1300:4e9:f8d0:2b4a:8e5b:ee1f", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eChildren)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Screen_time"}
{"title_page": "John Clark Milne", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = John Clark Milne\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = 1897\n| birth_place = [[Memsie]], Aberdeenshire, Scotland\n| death_date  = 1962\n| death_place = \n| nationality = Scottish\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = ''The Orra Loon''\n| occupation  = Poet\n}}\n'''John Clark Milne''' (1897-1962) was a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] poet who wrote in the [[Doric dialect (Scotland)|Doric]] dialect of the [[Scots language]].\nHe was also a teacher and educationalist.{{sfn|McClure|2000|p=183}}\nSome of his poetry was written for children.{{sfn|MacGillivray|1997|p=37}}\n\n==Life==\n\nJohn Milne was born at [[Memsie]], near [[Fraserburgh]] in Aberdeenshire in 1897 to a farming family.\nHe attended the [[University of Aberdeen]] where he excelled academically, then became a teacher. \nIn later years he was Master of Method at Aberdeen College of Education. \nHis collection of verses, ''The Orra Loon'' was published in 1946 and his collected ''Poems'' in 1963.{{sfn|Henderson|1996}}\n\nThe northeastern poet and novelist [[Nan Shepherd]] helped prepare the latter edition of Milne's poetry, published after his death.{{sfn|Shepherd|2010|p=i}}\nIn 2009 the Buchan Heritage Society launched a CD on which well-known local performers and artists had collaborated in recording samples of his work.  The society hoped that through hearing Milne's unique poetry children would help preserve the Doric tongue, which many in the area have forgotten.{{sfn|Special concert}}\n\n==Work==\n\nAccording to Cuthbert Graham, \"The imaginative literature of Aberdeen for the past century has been dominated by a single theme&ndash;a single myth if you like in the deep psychological sense&ndash;a passion for the land... In poetry [[Charles Murray (poet)|Charles Murray]], John C. Milne and [[Flora Garry]] have illuminated the same obsessive concern.\"{{sfn|Orsman|1993|p=180-181}}\nJ.C. Milne's work was full of humorous irony, through which he could express his unique viewpoint while apparently reporting the speech of the characters he depicted.{{sfn|Aberdeen university review|p=347}}\nMilne had an extraordinary ability to exploit the potential for rhyming in the dialect.{{sfn|Caie|Hough|Wotherspoon|2006|p=99}}\nRich in vocabulary, his poetry seemed simple and unaffected.{{sfn|Caie|Hough|Wotherspoon|2006|p=100}}\nA snatch of Milne's poetry, with the wonderful word \"contermashious\", meaning \"contrary\":\n:O Lord look doon on Buchan\n:An a' its fairmer chiels!\n:For there's nae in a' Yer warld\n:Mair contermashious deils!{{sfn|Doric}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last=Milne|first=John Clark\n |title=THE ORRA LOON and Other Poems\n |publisher=Geo E. Findlay & Co Ltd |year=1946}}\n*{{cite book|last=Milne|first=John Clark\n |title=Poems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RtzHAAAACAAJ|accessdate=2012-07-26\n |year=1963|publisher=Aberdeen University Press|isbn=978-0-900015-35-9}}\n*{{cite book|last=Milne|first=J. C.|title=Poems of J C Milne\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9L4cAAAACAAJ|accessdate=2012-07-26\n |year=1964|publisher=VUB Gilde-Buchhandlung GmbH & Company KG|isbn=978-0-08-023629-2}}\n\n==References==\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist |colwidth=30em}}\n'''Sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{harvid|Aberdeen university review}}|title=Aberdeen university review\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zXdYAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2012-07-26\n |year=1977|publisher=Aberdeen University Press.}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv\n |last1=Caie|first1=Graham D.|last2=Hough|first2=Carole|last3=Wotherspoon|first3=Iren\u00e9\n |title=The Power of Words: Essays in Lexicography, Lexicology and Semantics : in Honour of Christian J. Kay\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RfxcbpXhCZoC&pg=PA99|accessdate=2012-07-26\n |year=2006|publisher=Rodopi|isbn=978-90-420-2121-1|pages=99\u2013}}\n*{{cite web |ref={{harvid|Doric}} |url=http://www.mcs.st-and.ac.uk/~gmp/gmpDORIC.html\n |title=Doric - the dialect of North-East Scotland\n |publisher=School of Mathematics and Statistics at the University of St Andrews\n |accessdate=2012-07-26}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv\n |editor-first1=Christine |editor-last1=Franzen |editor-first2=Laurie |editor-last2=Bauer |title=Of Pavlova, Poetry and Paradigms: Essays in Honour of Harry Orsman\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hm-hXVgYBaEC&pg=PA180|accessdate=2012-07-26\n |year=1993|publisher=Victoria University Press|isbn=978-0-86473-247-7}}\n*{{cite web |ref=harv |url=http://www.electricscotland.com/poetry/doric.htm\n |work=Electric Scotland\n |title=Doric Dialects and Doric Poets of North-East Scotland\n |last=Henderson|first=John |year=1996\n |accessdate=2012-07-26}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv\n |last=MacGillivray|first=Alan|title=Teaching Scottish Literature: Curriculum and Classroom Applications\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WDuYlv74iCcC&pg=PA37|accessdate=2012-07-26\n |year=1997|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|isbn=978-0-7486-0930-7}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv\n |last=McClure|first=J. Derrick|title=Language, poetry, and nationhood: Scots as a poetic language from 1878 to the present\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OARaAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2012-07-26\n |year=2000|publisher=Tuckwell Press|isbn=978-1-86232-071-0}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv\n |last=Shepherd|first=Nan|title=The Weatherhouse\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xC5YwBoP_pIC&pg=PR1|accessdate=2012-07-26\n |date=2010-07-01|publisher=Canongate Books|isbn=978-1-84767-802-7}}\n*{{cite web |ref={{harvid|Special concert}} |url=http://www.buchanobserver.co.uk/news/local-headlines/special-concert-launch-for-heritage-society-cd-1-128373\n |work=Buchan Observer\n |title=Special concert launch for heritage society CD\n |date=4 August 2009\n |accessdate=2012-07-26}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Milne, John Clark}}\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:Doric poets]]\n[[Category:People from Aberdeenshire]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish poets]]\n[[Category:Scottish male poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = John Clark Milne\n| image       = \n| alt         = \n| caption     = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = 1897\n| birth_place = [[Memsie]], Aberdeenshire, Scotland\n| death_date  = 1962\n| death_place = \n| nationality = Scottish\n| other_names = \n| known_for   = ''The Orra Loon''\n| occupation  = Poet\n}}\n'''John Clark Milne''' (1897-1962) was a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] poet who wrote in the [[Doric dialect (Scotland)|Doric]] dialect of the [[Scots language]].\nHe was also a teacher and educationalist.{{sfn|McClure|2000|p=183}}\nSome of his poetry was written for children.{{sfn|MacGillivray|1997|p=37}}\n\n==Life==\n\nJohn Milne was born at [[Memsie]], near [[Fraserburgh]] in Aberdeenshire in 1897 to a farming family.\nHe attended the [[University of Aberdeen]] where he excelled academically, then became a teacher. \nIn later years he was Master of Method at Aberdeen College of Education. \nHis collection of verses, ''The Orra Loon'' was published in 1946 and his collected ''Poems'' in 1963.{{sfn|Henderson|1996}}\n\nThe northeastern poet and novelist [[Nan Shepherd]] helped prepare the latter edition of Milne's poetry, published after his death.{{sfn|Shepherd|2010|p=i}}\nIn 2009 the Buchan Heritage Society launched a CD on which well-known local performers and artists had collaborated in recording samples of his work.  The society hoped that through hearing Milne's unique poetry children would help preserve the Doric tongue, which many in the area have forgotten.{{sfn|Special concert}}\n\n==Work==\n\nAccording to Cuthbert Graham, \"The imaginative literature of Aberdeen for the past century has been dominated by a single theme&ndash;a single myth if you like in the deep psychological sense&ndash;a passion for the land... In poetry [[Charles Murray (poet)|Charles Murray]], John C. Milne and [[Flora Garry]] have illuminated the same obsessive concern.\"{{sfn|Orsman|1993|p=180-181}}\nJ.C. Milne's work was full of humorous irony, through which he could express his unique viewpoint while apparently reporting the speech of the characters he depicted.{{sfn|Aberdeen university review|p=347}}\nMilne had an extraordinary ability to exploit the potential for rhyming in the dialect.{{sfn|Caie|Hough|Wotherspoon|2006|p=99}}\nRich in vocabulary, his poetry seemed simple and unaffected.{{sfn|Caie|Hough|Wotherspoon|2006|p=100}}\nA snatch of Milne's poetry, with the wonderful word \"contermashious\", meaning \"contrary\":\n:O Lord look doon on Buchan\n:An a' its fairmer chiels!\n:For there's nae in a' Yer warld\n:Mair contermashious deils!{{sfn|Doric}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n*{{cite book|last=Milne|first=John Clark\n |title=THE ORRA LOON and Other Poems\n |publisher=Geo E. Findlay & Co Ltd |year=1946}}\n*{{cite book|last=Milne|first=John Clark\n |title=Poems|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RtzHAAAACAAJ|accessdate=2012-07-26\n |year=1963|publisher=Aberdeen University Press|isbn=978-0-900015-35-9}}\n*{{cite book|last=Milne|first=J. C.|title=Poems of J C Milne\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9L4cAAAACAAJ|accessdate=2012-07-26\n |year=1964|publisher=VUB Gilde-Buchhandlung GmbH & Company KG|isbn=978-0-08-023629-2}}\n\n==References==\n'''Citations'''\n{{reflist |colwidth=30em}}\n'''Sources'''\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|ref={{harvid|Aberdeen university review}}|title=Aberdeen university review\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zXdYAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2012-07-26\n |year=1977|publisher=Aberdeen University Press.}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv\n |last1=Caie|first1=Graham D.|last2=Hough|first2=Carole|last3=Wotherspoon|first3=Iren\u00e9\n |title=The Power of Words: Essays in Lexicography, Lexicology and Semantics : in Honour of Christian J. Kay\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RfxcbpXhCZoC&pg=PA99|accessdate=2012-07-26\n |year=2006|publisher=Rodopi|isbn=978-90-420-2121-1|pages=99\u2013}}\n*{{cite web |ref={{harvid|Doric}} |url=http://www.mcs.st-and.ac.uk/~gmp/gmpDORIC.html\n |title=Doric - the dialect of North-East Scotland\n |publisher=School of Mathematics and Statistics at the University of St Andrews\n |accessdate=2012-07-26}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv\n |editor-first1=Christine |editor-last1=Franzen |editor-first2=Laurie |editor-last2=Bauer |title=Of Pavlova, Poetry and Paradigms: Essays in Honour of Harry Orsman\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hm-hXVgYBaEC&pg=PA180|accessdate=2012-07-26\n |year=1993|publisher=Victoria University Press|isbn=978-0-86473-247-7}}\n*{{cite web |ref=harv |url=http://www.electricscotland.com/poetry/doric.htm\n |work=Electric Scotland\n |title=Doric Dialects and Doric Poets of North-East Scotland\n |last=Henderson|first=John |year=1996\n |accessdate=2012-07-26}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv\n |last=MacGillivray|first=Alan|title=Teaching Scottish Literature: Curriculum and Classroom Applications\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WDuYlv74iCcC&pg=PA37|accessdate=2012-07-26\n |year=1997|publisher=Edinburgh University Press|isbn=978-0-7486-0930-7}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv\n |last=McClure|first=J. Derrick|title=Language, poetry, and nationhood: Scots as a poetic language from 1878 to the present\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OARaAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2012-07-26\n |year=2000|publisher=Tuckwell Press|isbn=978-1-86232-071-0}}\n*{{cite book |ref=harv\n |last=Shepherd|first=Nan|title=The Weatherhouse\n |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xC5YwBoP_pIC&pg=PR1|accessdate=2012-07-26\n |date=2010-07-01|publisher=Canongate Books|isbn=978-1-84767-802-7}}\n*{{cite web |ref={{harvid|Special concert}} |url=http://www.buchanobserver.co.uk/news/local-headlines/special-concert-launch-for-heritage-society-cd-1-128373\n |work=Buchan Observer\n |title=Special concert launch for heritage society CD\n |date=4 August 2009\n |accessdate=2012-07-26}}\n{{refend}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Milne, John Clark}}\n[[Category:1897 births]]\n[[Category:1962 deaths]]\n[[Category:Doric poets]]\n[[Category:People from Aberdeenshire]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Aberdeen]]\n[[Category:20th-century Scottish poets]]\n[[Category:Scottish male poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century British male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Clark_Milne"}
{"title_page": "Bushmaster XM-15", "text_new": "{{infobox weapon\n| name               = Bushmaster XM-15\n| image              = File:M4gery.jpg\n| image_size         = 200px\n| alt                = Bushmaster XM15-E2S M4 Style Carbine\n| caption            = Bushmaster XM15-E2S M4 Style Carbine\n| origin             = United States\n| type               = [[Semi-automatic firearm|Semi-automatic]] [[rifle]]/[[carbine]]/<br>[[AR-15 style rifle]]\n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_ranged          = yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service            = \n| used_by            = \n| wars               = \n<!-- Production history -->\n| designer           = \n| design_date        = \n| manufacturer       = [[Bushmaster Firearms International]]\n| unit_cost          = \n| production_date    = \n| number             = \n| variants           =\n<!-- General specifications -->\n| spec_label         = \n| weight             = {{convert|8.27|lb|kg|abbr=on}} (20\" barrel, without magazine) <ref name=\"McNab\">{{cite book|last1=McNab|first1=Chris|title=Sporting Guns: A Guide to the World's Rifles and Shotguns|date=2007|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=978-0312368234|page=173|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q1OC9UCwTtEC}}</ref>\n| length             = {{convert|38.25|in|cm|abbr=on}} (20\" barrel) \n| part_length        = {{convert|20|in|cm|abbr=on}} (rifle), {{convert|16|in|cm|abbr=on}} (carbine)\n| width              = \n| height             = \n| diameter           = \n| crew               = \n| passengers         =\n<!-- Ranged weapon specifications --> \n| cartridge          = \n| cartridge_weight   = \n| caliber            = [[.223 Remington]] / [[5.56\u00d745mm NATO]]\n| barrels            = \n| action             = [[Gas operated]], [[direct impingement]]\n| rate               = 45 rounds per minute (semi-auto)<ref name=\"opmanual\">[http://stevespages.com/pdf/bushmaster_xm15.pdf Bushmaster XM15 operating manual, 1999 revision: statistics are for Bushmaster XM15-E2S]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n| velocity           = {{convert|3260|ft/s|m/s}}\n| range              = {{convert|600|yd|m}}<ref name=\"opmanual\"/>\n| max_range          = {{convert|3,865|yd|m}}<ref name=\"opmanual\"/>\n| feed               = [[STANAG magazine]]s, 30 rounds<ref name=\"otheropmanual\">{{Cite web |url=https://support.bushmaster.com/01_XM-15_RIFLES/User_Manual# |title=Bushmaster XM15 and Carbon 15 user manual, 2005 revision |access-date=2016-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160811060344/https://support.bushmaster.com/01_XM-15_RIFLES/User_Manual# |archive-date=2016-08-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| sights             = A2-style front post<ref name=\"sales brochure\">[https://secure.viewer.zmags.com/publication/c506ea39#/c506ea39/6 Bushmaster Firearms 2016 sales brochure]</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Bushmaster XM-15''' series (or '''XM15'''<ref name=\"opmanual\"/>) is a line of [[AR-15 style semi-automatic rifle]]s, and [[carbine]]s, manufactured by [[Bushmaster Firearms International]].<ref name=\"McNab\"/> Variants include the [[Bushmaster M4-type Carbine]], Patrolman series, QRC series, Bushmaster XM15-E2S and the [[Carbon 15]] line.<ref name=\"McNab\"/><ref name=\"sales brochure\"/>\n\n==Variants==\nThe standard XM-15 has a forged 7075T6 aircraft-grade [[aluminum]] upper and lower receiver. Barrels of XM-15 firearms have a heavy profile and are hard chrome-lined [[41xx steel|4150 alloy steel]] or 416 [[stainless steel]].<ref name=\"McNab\"/><ref name=\"otheropmanual\"/> In Bushmaster's 2016 sales brochure, all new-production XM-15s are stated to be supplied with a 4150 steel barrel.<ref name=\"sales brochure\"/>  The standard barrel has rifling of 1 turn in 9\".<ref name=\"opmanual\"/>\n*E2S Series: The basic E2S is fitted with a 16-inch carbine-style barrel.\n**E2S Target<ref name=\"Catalog\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X0QACwAAQBAJ|title=2016 Standard Catalog of Firearms: The Collector's Price and Reference Guide|first=Jerry|last=Lee|date=29 January 2016|publisher=F+W Media, Inc.|via=Google Books|isbn=9781440244414}}</ref> - 20\" heavy-barrel target rifle with A2-style stock and carry handle upper, also available with 24\" and 26\" barrels.\n**E2S Shorty<ref name=\"Guns2011\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eT2t8PBVmVMC|title=Guns Illustrated 2011: The Latest Guns, Specs & Prices|first=Dan|last=Shideler|date=20 August 2010|publisher=F+W Media, Inc|via=Google Books|isbn=9781440216244}}</ref> - 16-inch version with a \"shorty\" handguard.<ref name=\"Catalog\"/>\n**E2S Shorty AK<ref name=\"Guns2011\"/> - Shorty variant with 14.5-inch carbine SBR barrel with an [[AK-74]]-style muzzle brake permanently welded to the end to increase the overall length to 16 inches.\n**E2S Dissipator<ref name=\"Guns2011\"/> - Variant with a Bushmaster-designed 16-inch \"Dissipator\" barrel. This mounts a false gas block with a front sight at the 20\" position with the real gas block in the carbine position and concealed under a rifle-length 12\" handguard.\n\n*QRC Series: Formerly known as ORC (\"optics ready carbine\"), but now styled as QRC (\"quick response carbine\"), are flat-top rifles without iron sights, provided with a simple 1x20 red-dot optic. QRC is chambered in 5.56x45mm with a 1:8 twist melonite coated barrel, M16 style bolt carrier group & mil-spec buffer tube.\n\n*Patrolman Series:<ref name=\"Catalog\"/> - 7\" or 10.5\" barrel \"pistol\" version with a free-float handguard and no stock. Also available as a military or LE select-fire version.\n\n*Bushmaster M4-Type Carbine\n{{main|Bushmaster M4-type Carbine}}\n\n*Carbon 15\n{{main|Carbon 15}}\n\n==Notoriety==\nAccording to [[Gregg Lee Carter]], an American sociologist who studies [[gun violence in the United States]], the firearm was designed to comply with the 1994 [[Federal Assault Weapons Ban]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Carter|first1=Gregg Lee|title=Gun Control in the United States: A Reference Handbook|date=2006|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9781851097609|page=[https://archive.org/details/guncontrolinunit0000cart/page/151 151]|url=https://archive.org/details/guncontrolinunit0000cart|url-access=registration|accessdate=24 August 2016|quote=The most infamous example is the Bushmaster ...rifle that John Allen Muhammed and John Lee Malvo use in their October 2002 Washington D.D., killing spree. }}</ref> The Bushmaster XM15-E2S \"M4 type\" carbine gained notoriety for its use in the October 2002 [[Beltway sniper attacks]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harrison|first1=Judy|title=Colt's federal suit against rival firearm firm gets moved to Maine|agency=Knight Ridder Tribune Business News|date=11 Nov 2004|quote=Bushmaster's XM-15 E2s \"M4 type\" carbine allegedly was used by John Allen Muhammad and has gained notoriety as the weapon used in the Washington, D.C., area sniper shootings, according to the complaint.}}</ref> \n\nA Bushmaster XM-15 was used in the December 2012 [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lysiak|first1=Matthew|title=Video of Adam Lanza Confirmed as Newtown Parents Sue|url=http://www.newsweek.com/sandy-hook-lawsuit-adam-lanza-429526|accessdate=23 February 2016|work=Newsweek|publisher=Newsweek LLC|date=23 Feb 2016}}</ref> Just before the two-year anniversary of the massacre, nine families of the 26 victims of the shooting filed a class action lawsuit in Connecticut against Bushmaster, [[Remington Arms]] and others,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-sandy-hook-gun-lawsuit-20141215-story.html|title=Sandy Hook Families' Suit Against Gun Maker Will Test Federal Law|last=ALTIMARI|first=By DAVE|website=courant.com|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> seeking \"unspecified\" damages for the defendants' purported negligent entrustment and illegal marketing of the XM-15 rifle.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|last1=Fantz|first1=Ashley|title=Gun makers urge judge to toss Sandy Hook lawsuit|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/06/20/health/sandy-hook-newtown-gun-lawsuit/|work=CNN|publisher=CNN LLC|date=20 June 2016}}</ref> Plaintiffs argued that both theories of liability fell within exceptions to the 2005 [[Protection of Lawful Commerce in Arms Act]], which affords broad civil immunity to gun manufacturers.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Terrill|first1=Daniel|title=Remington tries for dismissal in Sandy Hook, Bushmaster case|url=http://www.guns.com/2016/02/22/remington-lawyers-try-for-dismissal-in-sandy-hook-bushmaster-case/|website=Guns.com|accessdate=23 February 2016|date=2016-02-22}}</ref><ref name=\"obbieatlantic\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/02/bushmaster-sandy-hook-liability/463245/|title=Will a Gun Manufacturer Be Held Liable for Sandy Hook?|last1=Obbie|first1=Mark|date=17 Feb 2016|work=The Atlantic|accessdate=23 February 2016|publisher=The Atlantic Monthly Group}}</ref> The case was dismissed in superior court and was appealed to the Connecticut Supreme Court. <ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Alex|title=Fate of Sandy Hook lawsuit against gun maker could be decided by a slingshot|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/fate-sandy-hook-lawsuit-against-gun-maker-could-be-decided-n820776|accessdate=May 2, 2018|publisher=NBC News}}</ref> In March 2019, the Connecticut Supreme Court reinstated the wrongful death lawsuit, holding that the plaintiffs successfully pleaded a cause of action for illegal marketing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Collins |first1=Dave |title=Court rules gun maker can be sued over Newtown shooting |url=https://apnews.com/a4b101a04dc9469999880a61280fd0da |accessdate=5 September 2019 |work=AP News |publisher=The Associated Press |date=14 March 2019}}</ref> Remington appealed to the United States Supreme Court, which denied review on November 12, 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/12/us/politics/supreme-court-sandy-hook-remington.html|title=Supreme Court Allows Sandy Hook Relatives to Sue Gun Maker|last=Hussey|first=Kristin|date=2019-11-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-31|last2=Williamson|first2=Elizabeth|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The trial is scheduled for September 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-news-sandy-hook-gun-case-restart-20191211-datpilvvmbfgrniveeshbzt5hq-story.html|title=After long delay, lawsuit by Sandy Hook families against gun maker Remington Arms will go to trial in 2021|last=Altimari|first=Dave|website=courant.com|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\nAn XM-15 was also used in the 2018 [[Nashville Waffle House shooting]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Amir Vera |date=April 22, 2018 |url=https://amp.cnn.com/cnn/2018/04/22/us/waffle-house-shooter-white-house/index.html |title=Waffle House shooter was once arrested by Secret Service for trespassing near White House |publisher=CNN |accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Legality==\n\nAs a result of the [[Sandy Hook school shooting]]: \n* New York State banned the XM-15 series and [[assault weapon]]s in the January 2013 [[NY SAFE Act]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/16/nyregion/tougher-gun-law-in-new-york.html|title=Tougher Gun Law in New York|last=Kaplan|first=Thomas|date=2013-01-15|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref>\n\n==Users==\n*{{BRA}}: [[Federal Police of Brazil]]<ref>{{cite web |title=POTD: Brazilian Federal Police with Bushmaster XM15-E2S - |url=https://www.thefirearmblog.com/blog/2019/04/02/potd-brazilian-federal-police-with-bushmaster-xm15a2/ |website=The Firearm Blog |accessdate=23 July 2019 |date=2 April 2019}}</ref>\n*{{GEO}}\n*{{flagdeco|ISIL}} [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]<ref name=\"CAR 2014\" />\n*{{NZL}}: [[New Zealand Police]]<ref>https://www.police.govt.nz/news/release/1923</ref>\n*{{PNG}}<ref>{{cite book |title=The politics of destroying surplus small arms : inconspicuous disarmament |date=2010 |publisher=Alpers, Philip |isbn=978-0-415-49461-8 |pages=168\u2013169 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Under the gun : the small arms challenge in the Pacific |publisher=Victoria University Press in association with the Peace and Disarmament Education Trust |isbn=9780864734532 |pages=64\u201365}}</ref>\n*{{POL}}: Used by [[JW GROM]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Fot. 12. 5,56-mm kbk M4A1 firmy Bushmaster (XM-15-E2S) z 40-mm granatnikiem... - Ireneusz Chloupek Special-Ops.pl - Portal Ludzi Akcji |url=http://www.special-ops.pl/artykul-galeria/id534,arsenal-grom-1?gal=1&zdjecie=4862 |website=Special-Ops.pl - Portal Ludzi Akcji |accessdate=23 July 2019 |language=pl}}</ref>\n*{{USA}}\n**{{flagicon image|Flag of Boston.svg}} [[Boston Police Special Operations Unit]]\n**{{flagicon image|Flag of Cincinnati, Ohio.svg}} [[Cincinnati Police Department]]\n**{{flagicon image|Flag of the United States Fish and Wildlife Service.svg}} [[United States Fish & Wildlife Service]]\n\n==References==\n \t\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{wikiquote}}\n\n{{Bushmaster Firearms International}}\n{{ArmaLite AR-10 derivatives}}\n[[Category:5.56 mm firearms]]\n[[Category:Rifles of the United States]]\n[[Category:Semi-automatic rifles]]\n[[Category:Bushmaster firearms]]\n[[Category:ArmaLite AR-10 derivatives]]\n[[Category:AR-15 style rifles]]\n", "text_old": "{{infobox weapon\n| name               = Bushmaster XM-15\n| image              = File:M4gery.jpg\n| image_size         = 200px\n| alt                = Bushmaster XM15-E2S M4 Style Carbine\n| caption            = Bushmaster XM15-E2S M4 Style Carbine\n| origin             = United States\n| type               = [[Semi-automatic firearm|Semi-automatic]] [[rifle]]/[[carbine]]/<br>[[AR-15 style rifle]]\n<!-- Type selection -->\n| is_ranged          = yes\n<!-- Service history -->\n| service            = \n| used_by            = \n| wars               = \n<!-- Production history -->\n| designer           = \n| design_date        = \n| manufacturer       = [[Bushmaster Firearms International]]\n| unit_cost          = \n| production_date    = \n| number             = \n| variants           =\n<!-- General specifications -->\n| spec_label         = \n| weight             = {{convert|8.27|lb|kg|abbr=on}} (20\" barrel, without magazine) <ref name=\"McNab\">{{cite book|last1=McNab|first1=Chris|title=Sporting Guns: A Guide to the World's Rifles and Shotguns|date=2007|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=978-0312368234|page=173|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=q1OC9UCwTtEC}}</ref>\n| length             = {{convert|38.25|in|cm|abbr=on}} (20\" barrel) \n| part_length        = {{convert|20|in|cm|abbr=on}} (rifle), {{convert|16|in|cm|abbr=on}} (carbine)\n| width              = \n| height             = \n| diameter           = \n| crew               = \n| passengers         =\n<!-- Ranged weapon specifications --> \n| cartridge          = \n| cartridge_weight   = \n| caliber            = [[.223 Remington]] / [[5.56\u00d745mm NATO]]\n| barrels            = \n| action             = [[Gas operated]], [[direct impingement]]\n| rate               = 45 rounds per minute (semi-auto)<ref name=\"opmanual\">[http://stevespages.com/pdf/bushmaster_xm15.pdf Bushmaster XM15 operating manual, 1999 revision: statistics are for Bushmaster XM15-E2S]{{Dead link|date=November 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n| velocity           = {{convert|3260|ft/s|m/s}}\n| range              = {{convert|600|yd|m}}<ref name=\"opmanual\"/>\n| max_range          = {{convert|3,865|yd|m}}<ref name=\"opmanual\"/>\n| feed               = [[STANAG magazine]]s, 30 rounds<ref name=\"otheropmanual\">{{Cite web |url=https://support.bushmaster.com/01_XM-15_RIFLES/User_Manual# |title=Bushmaster XM15 and Carbon 15 user manual, 2005 revision |access-date=2016-07-24 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160811060344/https://support.bushmaster.com/01_XM-15_RIFLES/User_Manual# |archive-date=2016-08-11 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| sights             = A2-style front post<ref name=\"sales brochure\">[https://secure.viewer.zmags.com/publication/c506ea39#/c506ea39/6 Bushmaster Firearms 2016 sales brochure]</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''Bushmaster XM-15''' series (or '''XM15'''<ref name=\"opmanual\"/>) is a line of [[AR-15 style semi-automatic rifle]]s, and [[carbine]]s, manufactured by [[Bushmaster Firearms International]].<ref name=\"McNab\"/> Variants include the [[Bushmaster M4-type Carbine]], Patrolman series, QRC series, Bushmaster XM15-E2S and the [[Carbon 15]] line.<ref name=\"McNab\"/><ref name=\"sales brochure\"/>\n\n==Variants==\nThe standard XM-15 has a forged 7075T6 aircraft-grade [[aluminum]] upper and lower receiver. Barrels of XM-15 firearms have a heavy profile and are hard chrome-lined [[41xx steel|4150 alloy steel]] or 416 [[stainless steel]].<ref name=\"McNab\"/><ref name=\"otheropmanual\"/> In Bushmaster's 2016 sales brochure, all new-production XM-15s are stated to be supplied with a 4150 steel barrel.<ref name=\"sales brochure\"/>  The standard barrel has rifling of 1 turn in 9\".<ref name=\"opmanual\"/>\n*E2S Series: The basic E2S is fitted with a 16-inch carbine-style barrel.\n**E2S Target<ref name=\"Catalog\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X0QACwAAQBAJ|title=2016 Standard Catalog of Firearms: The Collector's Price and Reference Guide|first=Jerry|last=Lee|date=29 January 2016|publisher=F+W Media, Inc.|via=Google Books|isbn=9781440244414}}</ref> - 20\" heavy-barrel target rifle with A2-style stock and carry handle upper, also available with 24\" and 26\" barrels.\n**E2S Shorty<ref name=\"Guns2011\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eT2t8PBVmVMC|title=Guns Illustrated 2011: The Latest Guns, Specs & Prices|first=Dan|last=Shideler|date=20 August 2010|publisher=F+W Media, Inc|via=Google Books|isbn=9781440216244}}</ref> - 16-inch version with a \"shorty\" handguard.<ref name=\"Catalog\"/>\n**E2S Shorty AK<ref name=\"Guns2011\"/> - Shorty variant with 14.5-inch carbine SBR barrel with an [[AK-74]]-style muzzle brake permanently welded to the end to increase the overall length to 16 inches.\n**E2S Dissipator<ref name=\"Guns2011\"/> - Variant with a Bushmaster-designed 16-inch \"Dissipator\" barrel. This mounts a false gas block with a front sight at the 20\" position with the real gas block in the carbine position and concealed under a rifle-length 12\" handguard.\n\n*QRC Series: Formerly known as ORC (\"optics ready carbine\"), but now styled as QRC (\"quick response carbine\"), are flat-top rifles without iron sights, provided with a simple 1x20 red-dot optic. QRC is chambered in 5.56x45mm with a 1:8 twist melonite coated barrel, M16 style bolt carrier group & mil-spec buffer tube.\n\n*Patrolman Series:<ref name=\"Catalog\"/> - 7\" or 10.5\" barrel \"pistol\" version with a free-float handguard and no stock. Also available as a military or LE select-fire version.\n\n*Bushmaster M4-Type Carbine\n{{main|Bushmaster M4-type Carbine}}\n\n*Carbon 15\n{{main|Carbon 15}}\n\n==Notoriety==\nAccording to [[Gregg Lee Carter]], an American sociologist who studies [[gun violence in the United States]], the firearm was designed to comply with the 1994 [[Federal Assault Weapons Ban]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Carter|first1=Gregg Lee|title=Gun Control in the United States: A Reference Handbook|date=2006|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9781851097609|page=[https://archive.org/details/guncontrolinunit0000cart/page/151 151]|url=https://archive.org/details/guncontrolinunit0000cart|url-access=registration|accessdate=24 August 2016|quote=The most infamous example is the Bushmaster ...rifle that John Allen Muhammed and John Lee Malvo use in their October 2002 Washington D.D., killing spree. }}</ref> The Bushmaster XM15-E2S \"M4 type\" carbine gained notoriety for its use in the October 2002 [[Beltway sniper attacks]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Harrison|first1=Judy|title=Colt's federal suit against rival firearm firm gets moved to Maine|agency=Knight Ridder Tribune Business News|date=11 Nov 2004|quote=Bushmaster's XM-15 E2s \"M4 type\" carbine allegedly was used by John Allen Muhammad and has gained notoriety as the weapon used in the Washington, D.C., area sniper shootings, according to the complaint.}}</ref> \n\nA Bushmaster XM-15 was used in the December 2012 [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lysiak|first1=Matthew|title=Video of Adam Lanza Confirmed as Newtown Parents Sue|url=http://www.newsweek.com/sandy-hook-lawsuit-adam-lanza-429526|accessdate=23 February 2016|work=Newsweek|publisher=Newsweek LLC|date=23 Feb 2016}}</ref> Just before the two-year anniversary of the massacre, nine families of the 26 victims of the shooting filed a class action lawsuit in Connecticut against Bushmaster, [[Remington Arms]] and others,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-sandy-hook-gun-lawsuit-20141215-story.html|title=Sandy Hook Families' Suit Against Gun Maker Will Test Federal Law|last=ALTIMARI|first=By DAVE|website=courant.com|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> seeking \"unspecified\" damages for the defendants' purported negligent entrustment and illegal marketing of the XM-15 rifle.<ref name=\"CNN\">{{cite news|last1=Fantz|first1=Ashley|title=Gun makers urge judge to toss Sandy Hook lawsuit|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2016/06/20/health/sandy-hook-newtown-gun-lawsuit/|work=CNN|publisher=CNN LLC|date=20 June 2016}}</ref> Plaintiffs argued that both theories of liability fell within exceptions to the 2005 [[Protection of Lawful Commerce in Arms Act]], which affords broad civil immunity to gun manufacturers.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Terrill|first1=Daniel|title=Remington tries for dismissal in Sandy Hook, Bushmaster case|url=http://www.guns.com/2016/02/22/remington-lawyers-try-for-dismissal-in-sandy-hook-bushmaster-case/|website=Guns.com|accessdate=23 February 2016|date=2016-02-22}}</ref><ref name=\"obbieatlantic\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/02/bushmaster-sandy-hook-liability/463245/|title=Will a Gun Manufacturer Be Held Liable for Sandy Hook?|last1=Obbie|first1=Mark|date=17 Feb 2016|work=The Atlantic|accessdate=23 February 2016|publisher=The Atlantic Monthly Group}}</ref> The case was dismissed in superior court and was appealed to the Connecticut Supreme Court. <ref>{{cite news|last1=Johnson|first1=Alex|title=Fate of Sandy Hook lawsuit against gun maker could be decided by a slingshot|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/fate-sandy-hook-lawsuit-against-gun-maker-could-be-decided-n820776|accessdate=May 2, 2018|publisher=NBC News}}</ref> In March 2019, the Connecticut Supreme Court reinstated the wrongful death lawsuit, holding that the plaintiffs successfully pleaded a cause of action for illegal marketing.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Collins |first1=Dave |title=Court rules gun maker can be sued over Newtown shooting |url=https://apnews.com/a4b101a04dc9469999880a61280fd0da |accessdate=5 September 2019 |work=AP News |publisher=The Associated Press |date=14 March 2019}}</ref> Remington appealed to the United States Supreme Court, which denied review on November 12, 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/12/us/politics/supreme-court-sandy-hook-remington.html|title=Supreme Court Allows Sandy Hook Relatives to Sue Gun Maker|last=Hussey|first=Kristin|date=2019-11-12|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-12-31|last2=Williamson|first2=Elizabeth|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The trial is scheduled for September 2021.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/news/connecticut/hc-news-sandy-hook-gun-case-restart-20191211-datpilvvmbfgrniveeshbzt5hq-story.html|title=After long delay, lawsuit by Sandy Hook families against gun maker Remington Arms will go to trial in 2021|last=Altimari|first=Dave|website=courant.com|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\nAn XM-15 was also used in the 2018 [[Nashville Waffle House shooting]].<ref>{{cite news |author=Amir Vera |date=April 22, 2018 |url=https://amp.cnn.com/cnn/2018/04/22/us/waffle-house-shooter-white-house/index.html |title=Waffle House shooter was once arrested by Secret Service for trespassing near White House |publisher=CNN |accessdate=April 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nAn XM15-E2 was captured from [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant|Islamic State]] fighters in [[Sinjar Mountains]] by [[Peshmerga]] during the [[Iraqi Civil War (2014\u20132017)|Iraqi Civil War]]. <ref name =\"CAR 2014\">{{cite book|title=Islamic State Weapons in Iraq and Syria: Analysis of weapons and ammunition captured from Islamic State forces in Iraq and Syria|url=http://conflictarm.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/09/Dispatch_IS_Iraq_Syria_Weapons.pdf|date=September 2014|author=Conflict Armament Research|pages=12\u201314|ref={{harvid|Conflict Armament Research 2014}}|author-link=Conflict Armament Research}}</ref>\n\n==Legality==\n\nAs a result of the [[Sandy Hook school shooting]]: \n* New York State banned the XM-15 series and [[assault weapon]]s in the January 2013 [[NY SAFE Act]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/01/16/nyregion/tougher-gun-law-in-new-york.html|title=Tougher Gun Law in New York|last=Kaplan|first=Thomas|date=2013-01-15|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|access-date=2016-09-14}}</ref>\n* The XM-15 series are among over 100 named firearms added to the [[Assault weapons legislation in the United States#Connecticut|Connecticut state assault weapon ban]] list in an April 2013 amendment, passed in the wake of the Sandy Hook school shooting.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.ct.gov/despp/lib/despp/slfu/firearms/assault_weapons.pdf |title = Department of Emergency Services and Public Protection}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/04/05/nyregion/connecticut-lawmakers-pass-gun-limits.html |title = Connecticut Governor Signs Gun Measures|newspaper = The New York Times|date = 2013-04-04}}</ref>\n\n==Users==\n*{{BRA}}: [[Federal Police of Brazil]]<ref>{{cite web |title=POTD: Brazilian Federal Police with Bushmaster XM15-E2S - |url=https://www.thefirearmblog.com/blog/2019/04/02/potd-brazilian-federal-police-with-bushmaster-xm15a2/ |website=The Firearm Blog |accessdate=23 July 2019 |date=2 April 2019}}</ref>\n*{{GEO}}\n*{{flagdeco|ISIL}} [[Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant]]<ref name=\"CAR 2014\" />\n*{{NZL}}: [[New Zealand Police]]<ref>https://www.police.govt.nz/news/release/1923</ref>\n*{{PNG}}<ref>{{cite book |title=The politics of destroying surplus small arms : inconspicuous disarmament |date=2010 |publisher=Alpers, Philip |isbn=978-0-415-49461-8 |pages=168\u2013169 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Under the gun : the small arms challenge in the Pacific |publisher=Victoria University Press in association with the Peace and Disarmament Education Trust |isbn=9780864734532 |pages=64\u201365}}</ref>\n*{{POL}}: Used by [[JW GROM]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Fot. 12. 5,56-mm kbk M4A1 firmy Bushmaster (XM-15-E2S) z 40-mm granatnikiem... - Ireneusz Chloupek Special-Ops.pl - Portal Ludzi Akcji |url=http://www.special-ops.pl/artykul-galeria/id534,arsenal-grom-1?gal=1&zdjecie=4862 |website=Special-Ops.pl - Portal Ludzi Akcji |accessdate=23 July 2019 |language=pl}}</ref>\n*{{USA}}\n**{{flagicon image|Flag of Boston.svg}} [[Boston Police Special Operations Unit]]\n**{{flagicon image|Flag of Cincinnati, Ohio.svg}} [[Cincinnati Police Department]]\n**{{flagicon image|Flag of the United States Fish and Wildlife Service.svg}} [[United States Fish & Wildlife Service]]\n\n==References==\n \t\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{wikiquote}}\n\n{{Bushmaster Firearms International}}\n{{ArmaLite AR-10 derivatives}}\n[[Category:5.56 mm firearms]]\n[[Category:Rifles of the United States]]\n[[Category:Semi-automatic rifles]]\n[[Category:Bushmaster firearms]]\n[[Category:ArmaLite AR-10 derivatives]]\n[[Category:AR-15 style rifles]]\n", "name_user": "198.161.136.20", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eLegality)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bushmaster_XM-15"}
{"title_page": "John Chabot Smith", "text_new": "'''John Chabot Smith''' (1915-2002) was an American journalist and author, best known for ''[[Alger Hiss]]:  The True Story'', an account sympathetic to Hiss.<ref name=Princeton>\n{{cite journal\n| title = Memorial: John Chabot Smith '36\n| journal = Princeton Alumni Weekly\n| url = https://paw.princeton.edu/memorial/john-chabot-smith-\u201936\n| date = 25 November 1976\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=NYTobit>\n{{cite journal\n| title = Smith, John Chabot\n| journal = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2002/05/18/classified/paid-notice-deaths-smith-john-chabot.html\n| date = 18 May 2002\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=Kirkus>\n{{cite journal\n| title = Alger Hiss: The True Story\n| journal = Kirkus\n| url = https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/john-chabot-smith/alger-hiss-the-true-story/\n| date = 22 May 1976\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nJohn Chabot Smith was born on September 1, 1915, in [[Croydon]], UK.  He attended [[Loomis Chaffee|the Loomis Institute]].  He majored in history at [[Princeton University]].  He did graduate studies at [[Cambridge University]].<ref name=Princeton/>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Elizabeth Bentley.jpg|thumb|right|[[Elizabeth Bentley]] (1948), ex-Soviet spy whom Smith covered]]\nSmith began his career as a journalist with the ''[[Washington Post]]''.  He joined the ''[[New York Herald Tribune]]'' as White House correspondent.<ref name=Princeton/><ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=Kirkus/>\n\nSmith covered [[World War II]] overseas for the Herald-Trib.<ref name=Princeton/><ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=Kirkus/>  [[Leon Dennen]] called him a \"pro-[[Josip Broz Tito|Tito]] correspondent.\"<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = Leon\n| last = Dennen\n| authorlink = Leon Dennen\n| title = Trouble zone: brewing point of World War III?\n| publisher = Ziff-Davis\n| url = https://archive.org/details/troublezonebrewi00denn\n| url-access = registration\n| page = [https://archive.org/details/troublezonebrewi00denn/page/102 102]\n| date = 1945\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nSmith covered [[Elizabeth Bentley]].<ref name=Bentley>\n{{cite journal\n| first = John Chabot\n| last = Smith\n| authorlink = John Chabot Smith\n| title = Woman Informer Against Reds Is Called by Thomas Committee\n| journal = New York Herald Tribune\n| url = \n| date = 29 July 1948\n}}</ref>\n\nSmith covered the Hiss Case for the Herald Trib and later wrote a book about it, and about Hiss\u2019s life in general.<ref name=Kirkus/>  Three other journalists who covered the case also published books about it:  [[Bert Andrews (journalist)|Bert Andrews]] of Hearst, [[Ralph de Toledano]] of ''[[Newsweek]]'', and [[Alistair Cooke]] of the ''Manchester [[The Guardian|Guardian]]''.\n\nHiss appeared with Smith at a press conference to promote the book, held at the [[Overseas Press Club]].<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = G. Edward\n| last = White\n| title = Alger Hiss's Looking-glass Wars: The Covert Life of a Soviet Spy\n| publisher = Oxford University Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=jH08DwAAQBAJ\n| page = xiv\n| date = 2005\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018| isbn = 9780195182552\n}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and death==\n\nIn 1940, Smith married Betty McCarthy; they had two children.  She predeceased him.<ref name=Princeton/><ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nSmith died age 86 on May 16, 2002, in Brooklyn, New York.<ref name=Princeton/><ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n==Works==\n[[File:Alger Hiss (1950).jpg|thumb|right|[[Alger Hiss]] (1950), (alleged) ex-Soviet spy about whom Smith wrote his best known book]]\nOf his book on Alger Hiss, Kirkus noted:  \"Don't expect bombshells. The hard evidence is slow in coming and can be bewilderingly technical when it come.\"<ref name=Kirkus/>  According to [[Allen Weinstein]] (whose book ''[[Perjury: The Hiss\u2013Chambers Case]]'', published in 1978, had different findings), \"Smith adopted elements from a least six previous theories.<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = Allen\n| last = Weinstein\n| authorlink = Allen Weinstein\n| title = Perjury: The Hiss Chambers Case\n| publisher = Knopf\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=toEfF8xlMmkC\n| page = 558\n| date = 1978\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018| isbn = 9780394495460\n}}</ref>  The ''Western Journal of Speech Communications'' assessed the book as \"thoroughly sympathetic\" Hiss.<ref>\n{{cite book\n| title = Western Journal of Speech Communications\n| publisher = Taylor & Francis| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=g943AAAAIAAJ\n| page = 98\n| date = 1984\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Books include===\n* ''Alger Hiss:  The True Story'' (1976)<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = John Chabot\n| last = Smith\n| authorlink = John Chabot Smith\n| title = Alger Hiss Chambers Case\n| publisher = Holt, Rinehart and Winston\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=bCYrAAAAIAAJ\n| page = \n| date = 1976\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018| isbn = 9780030137761\n}}</ref>\n* ''The Children of Master O'Rourke: An Irish Family Sage'' (1977)<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = John Chabot\n| last = Smith\n| authorlink = John Chabot Smith\n| title = The children of Master O'Rourke: an Irish family saga\n| publisher = Holt, Rinehart and Winston\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=toEfF8xlMmkC\n| page = \n| date = 1 September 1977\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018| isbn = 9780394495460\n}}</ref>\n\n===Articles include===\n* \u201dWoman Informer Against Reds Is Called by Thomas Committee\" ''New York Herald Tribune'' (29 July 1948)<ref name=Bentley/>\n* \"On Alger Hiss\" ''New York Review of Books'' (25 November 1976)<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| first = John Chabot\n| last = Smith\n| authorlink = John Chabot Smith\n| title = On Alger Hiss\n| journal = New York Review of Books\n| url = https://www.nybooks.com/articles/1976/11/25/on-alger-hiss/\n| date = 25 November 1976\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018}}</ref>\n* \"The Debate of the Century\" ''Harper's Magazine'' (June 1978)<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| first = John Chabot\n| last = Smith\n| authorlink = John Chabot Smith\n| title = The Debate of the Century\n| journal = Harper's Magazine\n| url = https://harpers.org/archive/1978/06/the-debate-of-the-century-cont/\n| date = June 1978\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alger Hiss]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, John Chabot}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:New York Herald Tribune people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n", "text_old": "'''John Chabot Smith''' (1915-2002) was an American journalist and author, best known for ''[[Alger Hiss]]:  The True Story'', an account sympathetic to Hiss.<ref name=Princeton>\n{{cite journal\n| title = Memorial: John Chabot Smith '36\n| journal = Princeton Alumni Weekly\n| url = https://paw.princeton.edu/memorial/john-chabot-smith-\u201936\n| date = 25 November 1976\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=NYTobit>\n{{cite journal\n| title = Smith, John Chabot\n| journal = New York Times\n| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2002/05/18/classified/paid-notice-deaths-smith-john-chabot.html\n| date = 18 May 2002\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018}}</ref><ref name=Kirkus>\n{{cite journal\n| title = Alger Hiss: The True Story\n| journal = Kirkus\n| url = https://www.kirkusreviews.com/book-reviews/john-chabot-smith/alger-hiss-the-true-story/\n| date = 22 May 1976\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n\nJohn Chabot Smith was born on September 1, 1915, in [[Croydon]], UK.  He attended [[Loomis Chaffee|the Loomis Institute]].  He majored in history at [[Princeton University]].  He did graduate studies at [[Cambridge University]].<ref name=Princeton/>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Elizabeth Bentley.jpg|thumb|right|[[Elizabeth Bentley]] (1948), ex-Soviet spy whom Smith covered]]\nSmith began his career as a journalist with the ''[[Washington Post]]''.  He joined the ''[[New York Herald Tribune]]'' as White House correspondent.<ref name=Princeton/><ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=Kirkus/>\n\nSmith covered [[World War II]] overseas for the Herald-Trib.<ref name=Princeton/><ref name=NYTobit/><ref name=Kirkus/>  [[Leon Dennen]] called him a \"pro-[[Josip Broz Tito|Tito]] correspondent.\"<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = Leon\n| last = Dennen\n| authorlink = Leon Dennen\n| title = Trouble zone: brewing point of World War III?\n| publisher = Ziff-Davis\n| url = https://archive.org/details/troublezonebrewi00denn\n| url-access = registration\n| page = [https://archive.org/details/troublezonebrewi00denn/page/102 102]\n| date = 1945\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nSmith covered [[Elizabeth Bentley]].<ref name=Bentley>\n{{cite journal\n| first = John Chabot\n| last = Smith\n| authorlink = John Chabot Smith\n| title = Woman Informer Against Reds Is Called by Thomas Committee\n| journal = New York Herald Tribune\n| url = \n| date = 29 July 1948\n}}</ref>\n\nSmith covered the Hiss Case for the Herald Trib and later wrote a book about it, and about Hiss\u2019s life in general.<ref name=Kirkus/>  Three other journalists who covered the case also published books about it:  [[Bert Andrews (journalist)|Bert Andrews]] of Hearst, [[Ralph de Toledano]] of ''[[Newsweek]]'', and [[Alistair Cooke]] of the ''Manchester [[The Guardian|Guardian]]''.\n\nHiss appeared with Smith at a press conference to promote the book, held at the [[Overseas Press Club]].<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = G. Edward\n| last = White\n| title = Alger Hiss's Looking-glass Wars: The Covert Life of a Soviet Spy\n| publisher = Oxford University Press\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=jH08DwAAQBAJ\n| page = xiv\n| date = 2005\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018| isbn = 9780195182552\n}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life and death==\n\nIn 1940, Smith married Betty McCarthy; they had two children.  She predeceased him.<ref name=Princeton/><ref name=NYTobit/>\n\nSmith died age 86 on May 16, 2002, in Brooklyn, New York.<ref name=Princeton/><ref name=NYTobit/>\n\n==Works==\n[[File:Alger Hiss (1950).jpg|thumb|right|[[Alger Hiss]] (1950), (alleged) ex-Soviet spy about whom Smith wrote his best known book]]\nOf his book on Alger Hiss, Kirkus noted:  \"Don't expect bombshells. The hard evidence is slow in coming and can be bewilderingly technical when it come.\"<ref name=Kirkus/>  According to [[Allen Weinstein]] (whose book ''[[Perjury: The Hiss\u2013Chambers Case]]'', published in 1978, had different findings), \"Smith adopted elements from a least six previous theories.<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = Allen\n| last = Weinstein\n| authorlink = Allen Weinstein\n| title = Perjury: The Hiss Chambers Case\n| publisher = Knopf\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=toEfF8xlMmkC\n| page = 558\n| date = 1978\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018| isbn = 9780394495460\n}}</ref>  The ''Western Journal of Speech Communications'' assessed the book as \"thoroughly sympathetic\" Hiss.<ref>\n{{cite book\n| title = Western Journal of Speech Communications\n| publisher = Taylor & Francis| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=g943AAAAIAAJ\n| page = 98\n| date = 1984\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Books include===\n* ''Alger Hiss:  The True Story'' (1976)<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = John Chabot\n| last = Smith\n| authorlink = John Chabot Smith\n| title = Alger Hiss Chambers Case\n| publisher = Holt, Rinehart and Winston\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=bCYrAAAAIAAJ\n| page = \n| date = 1976\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018| isbn = 9780030137761\n}}</ref>\n* ''The Children of Master O'Rourke: An Irish Family Sage'' (1977)<ref>\n{{cite book\n| first = John Chabot\n| last = Smith\n| authorlink = John Chabot Smith\n| title = The children of Master O'Rourke: an Irish family saga\n| publisher = Holt, Rinehart and Winston\n| url = https://books.google.com/books?id=toEfF8xlMmkC\n| page = \n| date = 1 September 1977\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018| isbn = 9780394495460\n}}</ref>\n\n===Articles include===\n* \u201dWoman Informer Against Reds Is Called by Thomas Committee\" ''New York Herald Tribune'' (29 July 1948)<ref name=Bentley/>\n\n* \"On Alger Hiss\" ''New York Review of Books'' (25 November 1976)<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| first = John Chabot\n| last = Smith\n| authorlink = John Chabot Smith\n| title = On Alger Hiss\n| journal = New York Review of Books\n| url = https://www.nybooks.com/articles/1976/11/25/on-alger-hiss/\n| date = 25 November 1976\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018}}</ref>\n* \"The Debate of the Century\" ''Harper's Magazine'' (June 1978)<ref>\n{{cite journal\n| first = John Chabot\n| last = Smith\n| authorlink = John Chabot Smith\n| title = The Debate of the Century\n| journal = Harper's Magazine\n| url = https://harpers.org/archive/1978/06/the-debate-of-the-century-cont/\n| date = June 1978\n| accessdate = 17 October 2018}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Alger Hiss]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smith, John Chabot}}\n[[Category:1915 births]]\n[[Category:2002 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male journalists]]\n[[Category:New York Herald Tribune people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American journalists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American journalists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Chabot_Smith"}
{"title_page": "The Iron Orchard", "text_new": "{{short description|2018 drama film directed by Ty Roberts}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Iron Orchard\n| image          = File:The Iron Orchard (2018) Film Poster.jpg\n| caption        = [[Film poster]]\n| writer         = Gerry De Leon<br />Ty Roberts\n| starring       = \n{{Plainlist|\n* [[Austin Nichols]]\n* [[Lane Garrison]]\n* [[Ali Cobrin]]\n* Donny Boaz\n* [[Lew Temple]]\n}}\n| director       = Ty Roberts\n| producer       = Houston Hill<br />Ty Roberts<br />Camille Scioli-Mcnamara<br />George Sledge\n| cinematography = Mathieu Plainfoss\u00e9\n| editing        = James K. Crouch<br />Ty Roberts\n| music          = Duncan Thum\n| studio         = Santa Rita Film Co.<br />Wildcatters Network\n| distributor    = Santa Rita Film Co.\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|5|5|[[Dallas International Film Festival]]|2019|2|22|United States}}\n| runtime        = 112 minutes\n| country        = United States<br />Italy\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\nBased on the 1966 novel by Tom Pendleton<ref>https://www.tamupress.com/book/9780875657127/the-iron-orchard/</ref>, '''''The Iron Orchard''''' is a 2018 American historic-[[drama film]] co-written, co-produced and directed by Ty Roberts. The movie was first shown on May 5, 2018, at the [[Dallas International Film Festival]] and was [[Limited theatrical release|limited released]] on February 22, 2019, in the United States.\n\n==Plot==\nThe story of Jim McNeely who, in 1939, struggles to make it in the oil business.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Austin Nichols]] as Dent Paxton\n* [[Lane Garrison]] as Jim McNeely\n* [[Ali Cobrin]] as Lee Montgomery\n* Donny Boaz as Charlie Dupree\n* [[Lew Temple]] as Ort Cooley\n* Hassie Harrison as Mazie Wales\n* Harlan Whatley as Medical Doctor\n\n==Release==\n===Reception===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], The Iron Orchard has an approval rating of 28% based on 18 reviews.<ref name=\"The Iron Orchard - Rotten Tomatoes\">{{cite web |title=The Iron Orchard |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_iron_orchard |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], another review aggregator which uses a weighted average, assigned the film a score of 43 out of 100 based on 9 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\"<ref name=\"The Iron Orchard (2019) - Metacritic\">{{cite web |title=The Iron Orchard (2019) |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-iron-orchard |website=Metacritic |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nKimber Myers from the [[Los Angeles Times]] said that \"though there are some well-framed shots from cinematographer Mathieu Plainfoss\u00e9, the script from Gerry De Leon and director Ty Roberts is lifeless, covered in a layer of dust that the cast can't rouse it from.\"<ref name=\"Reviews: Supernatural 'Stray', dystopian 'Level 16', Jean-Claude Van Damme and more\">{{cite web |last1=Myers |first1=Kimber |title=Reviews: Supernatural 'Stray', dystopian 'Level 16', Jean-Claude Van Damme and more |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-capsule-3-review-string-20190229-story.html |website=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> Jeannette Catsoulis writing for [[The New York Times]] stated: \"Seemingly nostalgic for a period when West Texas roughnecks settled scores with baseball bats and laid pipe with pickaxes, this lovingly made homage to avarice feels strangely limp. Instead of gushing, it trickles.\"<ref name=\"\u2018The Iron Orchard\u2019 Review: Black Gold and Blackhearted Men\">{{cite web |last1=Catsoulis |first1=Jeannette |title=\u2018The Iron Orchard\u2019 Review: Black Gold and Blackhearted Men |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/28/movies/the-iron-orchard-review.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> American film critic and historian [[Joe Leydon]] liked the movie and his review for [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] wrote: \"Garrison strikes the perfect balance of cocksure swagger and not-so-quiet desperation while offering a credible and creditable portrayal of a man forever on the verge of plunging into the abyss because of the same instincts that initially fuel his ascent. He and supporting players Cobrin and Nichols help to make \u201cThe Iron Orchard\u201d an absorbing story, even if you wind up wishing more of that story had been told.\"<ref name=\"Film Review: \u2018The Iron Orchard\u2019\">{{cite web |last1=Leydon |first1=Joe |title=Film Review: \u2018The Iron Orchard\u2019 |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/the-iron-orchard-review-1203151444/ |website=Variety |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> [[Glenn Kenny]] from the [[RogerEbert.com]] gave Beneath the Leaves only 1.5 out of 5 stars and stated: \"As competently put together as this movie is, it imparted to me no sense of a higher calling, and thus left me unmoved.\"<ref name=\"The Iron Orchard - RogerEbert.com\">{{cite web |last1=Kenny |first1=Glenn |title=The Iron Orchard |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-iron-orchard-2019 |website=RogerEbert.com |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> [[Anthony Lane]] from the [[The New Yorker]] magazine also disliked the film, stating that \"the musical score is overcooked, the cast underpowered, and the dialogue something of a mishmash...\"<ref name=\"The Grim Rapacity of \u201cThe Iron Orchard\u201d\">{{cite web |last1=Lane |first1=Anthony |title=The Grim Rapacity of \"The Iron Orchard\" |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/03/04/the-grim-rapacity-of-the-iron-orchard |website=The New Yorker |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=tt7014234}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|the_iron_orchard}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iron Orchard, The}}\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2018 drama film directed by Ty Roberts}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Iron Orchard\n| image          = File:The Iron Orchard (2018) Film Poster.jpg\n| caption        = [[Film poster]]\n| writer         = Gerry De Leon<br />Ty Roberts\n| starring       = \n{{Plainlist|\n* [[Austin Nichols]]\n* [[Lane Garrison]]\n* [[Ali Cobrin]]\n* Donny Boaz\n* [[Lew Temple]]\n}}\n| director       = Ty Roberts\n| producer       = Houston Hill<br />Ty Roberts<br />Camille Scioli-Mcnamara<br />George Sledge\n| cinematography = Mathieu Plainfoss\u00e9\n| editing        = James K. Crouch<br />Ty Roberts\n| music          = Duncan Thum\n| studio         = Santa Rita Film Co.<br />Wildcatters Network\n| distributor    = Santa Rita Film Co.\n| released       = {{Film date|2018|5|5|[[Dallas International Film Festival]]|2019|2|22|United States}}\n| runtime        = 112 minutes\n| country        = United States<br />Italy\n| language       = English\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''The Iron Orchard''''' is a 2018 American historic-[[drama film]] co-written, co-produced and directed by Ty Roberts. The movie was first shown on May 5, 2018, at the [[Dallas International Film Festival]] and was [[Limited theatrical release|limited released]] on February 22, 2019, in the United States.\n\n==Plot==\nThe story of Jim McNeely who, in 1939, struggles to make it in the oil business.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Austin Nichols]] as Dent Paxton\n* [[Lane Garrison]] as Jim McNeely\n* [[Ali Cobrin]] as Lee Montgomery\n* Donny Boaz as Charlie Dupree\n* [[Lew Temple]] as Ort Cooley\n* Hassie Harrison as Mazie Wales\n* Harlan Whatley as Medical Doctor\n\n==Release==\n===Reception===\nOn [[review aggregator]] [[Rotten Tomatoes]], The Iron Orchard has an approval rating of 28% based on 18 reviews.<ref name=\"The Iron Orchard - Rotten Tomatoes\">{{cite web |title=The Iron Orchard |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/the_iron_orchard |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], another review aggregator which uses a weighted average, assigned the film a score of 43 out of 100 based on 9 critics, indicating \"mixed or average reviews\"<ref name=\"The Iron Orchard (2019) - Metacritic\">{{cite web |title=The Iron Orchard (2019) |url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-iron-orchard |website=Metacritic |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nKimber Myers from the [[Los Angeles Times]] said that \"though there are some well-framed shots from cinematographer Mathieu Plainfoss\u00e9, the script from Gerry De Leon and director Ty Roberts is lifeless, covered in a layer of dust that the cast can't rouse it from.\"<ref name=\"Reviews: Supernatural 'Stray', dystopian 'Level 16', Jean-Claude Van Damme and more\">{{cite web |last1=Myers |first1=Kimber |title=Reviews: Supernatural 'Stray', dystopian 'Level 16', Jean-Claude Van Damme and more |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/la-et-mn-capsule-3-review-string-20190229-story.html |website=Los Angeles Times |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> Jeannette Catsoulis writing for [[The New York Times]] stated: \"Seemingly nostalgic for a period when West Texas roughnecks settled scores with baseball bats and laid pipe with pickaxes, this lovingly made homage to avarice feels strangely limp. Instead of gushing, it trickles.\"<ref name=\"\u2018The Iron Orchard\u2019 Review: Black Gold and Blackhearted Men\">{{cite web |last1=Catsoulis |first1=Jeannette |title=\u2018The Iron Orchard\u2019 Review: Black Gold and Blackhearted Men |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/28/movies/the-iron-orchard-review.html |website=The New York Times |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> American film critic and historian [[Joe Leydon]] liked the movie and his review for [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] wrote: \"Garrison strikes the perfect balance of cocksure swagger and not-so-quiet desperation while offering a credible and creditable portrayal of a man forever on the verge of plunging into the abyss because of the same instincts that initially fuel his ascent. He and supporting players Cobrin and Nichols help to make \u201cThe Iron Orchard\u201d an absorbing story, even if you wind up wishing more of that story had been told.\"<ref name=\"Film Review: \u2018The Iron Orchard\u2019\">{{cite web |last1=Leydon |first1=Joe |title=Film Review: \u2018The Iron Orchard\u2019 |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/reviews/the-iron-orchard-review-1203151444/ |website=Variety |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> [[Glenn Kenny]] from the [[RogerEbert.com]] gave Beneath the Leaves only 1.5 out of 5 stars and stated: \"As competently put together as this movie is, it imparted to me no sense of a higher calling, and thus left me unmoved.\"<ref name=\"The Iron Orchard - RogerEbert.com\">{{cite web |last1=Kenny |first1=Glenn |title=The Iron Orchard |url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/the-iron-orchard-2019 |website=RogerEbert.com |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref> [[Anthony Lane]] from the [[The New Yorker]] magazine also disliked the film, stating that \"the musical score is overcooked, the cast underpowered, and the dialogue something of a mishmash...\"<ref name=\"The Grim Rapacity of \u201cThe Iron Orchard\u201d\">{{cite web |last1=Lane |first1=Anthony |title=The Grim Rapacity of \"The Iron Orchard\" |url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/03/04/the-grim-rapacity-of-the-iron-orchard |website=The New Yorker |accessdate=7 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=tt7014234}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|the_iron_orchard}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Iron Orchard, The}}\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n", "name_user": "Hdwhatley", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Iron_Orchard"}
{"title_page": "John Castriciones", "text_new": "{{Philippine name|Rualo|Castriciones}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = John Castriciones\n| image = John Castriciones 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Castriciones in 2018\n| order = \n| office = 14th [[Secretary of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Secretary of Agrarian Reform of the Philippines]]\n| term_start = December 1, 2017\n| term_end = \n| president = [[Rodrigo Duterte]]\n| predecessor = Rosalina Bistoyong\n| successor =\n| office2 = Undersecretary for Operations of the [[Department of the Interior and Local Government (Philippines)|Department of the Interior and Local Government]]\n| term_start2 = July 1, 2016\n| term_end2 = November 30, 2017\n| president2 = [[Rodrigo Duterte]]\n| predecessor2 = Rafael Santos\n| successor2 = Epimaco V. Densing III\n<!-- personal details -->\n| birth_name = John Rualo Castriciones\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1962|01|08}}\n| birth_place = [[Bayombong]], [[Nueva Vizcaya]], [[Philippines]]\n| nationality = [[Filipino people|Filipino]] \n| party = [[PDP\u2013Laban]]<br>[[Partido Federal ng Pilipinas]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = Lawyer, Professor\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Trinity University of Asia]] <br> {{small|(AB PolSci)}} <br/>[[Philippine Military Academy]]<br/>[[San Beda University]]<br/>[[Arellano University]] <br> {{small|(LL.B.)}} <br>[[University of Notre Dame]]\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| religion = \n| website = \n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''John Rualo Castriciones''' (born January 8, 1962) is a [[Filipino people|Filipino]] lawyer, public servant and writer who serves as the [[Secretary of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Secretary of Agrarian Reform]] of the [[Philippines]] since his appointment by President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] on December 1, 2017.<ref name=\"abs\">{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/12/01/17/duterte-names-dilg-exec-acting-agrarian-reform-chief |title=Duterte names DILG exec acting agrarian reform chief |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Placido, D. |date=1 December 2017 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> He was formerly Undersecretary for Operations of the [[Department of the Interior and Local Government (Philippines)|Department of the Interior and Local Government]] under the same administration.<ref name=\"dar\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dar.gov.ph/about-us/secretary |title=About the Secretary |publisher=[[Department of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)]] |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> A member of the [[Philippine Military Academy]] class of 1994, Castriciones also served in various capacities under two previous administrations and as a law school professor at his alma mater [[Arellano University]].<ref name=\"dar\"/><ref name=\"ca\"/> His appointment to the Agrarian Reform portfolio was approved by the [[Commission on Appointments]] on May 29, 2018, after being bypassed earlier by the commission on March 14, 2018 and reappointed by Duterte on March 22, 2018.<ref name=\"inq\">{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/995299/ca-body-confirms-dar-secretary-castriciones |title=CA body confirms DAR Secretary Castriciones |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Ager, M. |date=29 May 2018 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"pna\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1028644 |title=CA suspends confirmation of DAR Secretary |publisher=[[Philippine News Agency]] |author=Reganit, J.C. |date=14 March 2018 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/11/18/castriciones-reappointed-as-acting-dar-secretary |title=Castriciones reappointed as acting DAR secretary |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Ganibe, D. |date=11 April 2018 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nCastriciones is a native of the province of [[Nueva Vizcaya]]. He was born on January 8, 1962 to a family of farmers in the municipality of [[Bayombong]].<ref name=\"ca\">{{cite web|url=http://comappt.gov.ph/images/pdfiles/newarticle/PressRelease_30May.pdf |title=Cabinet Secretaries Castriciones, Romulo-Puyat, Guevarra, COMELEC Commissioner, DFA senior officials, AFP Chief and ranking officers breeze through the CA |publisher=[[Commission on Appointments]] |date=30 May 2018 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"pna\"/> As a young cadet-student at the [[Philippine Military Academy]] during [[Martial law under Ferdinand Marcos]], Castriciones was accused in the 1981 hazing death of fellow cadet Andres Ramos and was sentenced to five years of hard labor by a seven-man military court in July 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/08/15/world/philippine-military-academy-is-under-attack.html |title=Philippine Military Academy is under attack |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |author=Hollie, P. |date=15 August 1982 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> He was pardoned four year laters by the then newly-installed President [[Corazon Aquino]].<ref name=\"inq2\">{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/996778/http-newsinfo-inquirer-net-995819-poe-endorses-dar-chiefs-appointment-but-vows-to-watch-his-next-steps/amp |title=Courage slams confirmation of Castriciones as DAR chief |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Orellana, F. |date=2 June 2018 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nCastriciones then enrolled at the [[Trinity University of Asia]] in [[Quezon City]], formerly Trinity College, and graduated ''magna cum laude'' with a Political Science degree.<ref name=\"ca\"/> He went on to attend [[San Beda University]], former San Beda College, and [[Arellano University]] to pursue legal studies where he was consistenly in the Dean's List. Castriciones passed the [[Philippine Bar Examination]] in 1990.<ref name=\"dar\"/> He later earned an LL.M. master's degree in Comparative Government and International Law from [[Notre Dame Law School]] in [[London]], U.K. in 1998.<ref name=\"dar\"/><ref name=\"ca\"/>\n\nCastriciones finally completed his military training at the Philippine Military Academy in 1994 as part of the Maharlika Class.<ref name=\"dar\"/>\n\n==Career==\nCastriciones started practicing law in 1993 and has since litigated in both Inferior and Superior Courts, Administrative Bodies, Ombudsman and the [[Sandiganbayan]].<ref name=\"lbp\">{{cite web|url=https://www.landbank.com/node/180 |title=John R. Castriciones |publisher=[[Land Bank of the Philippines]] |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> He served as legal counsel for several corporations and government officials in his more than 20 years of private law practice. Castriciones eventually founded his own law firm, the Castriciones Legal Consultancy, where his lawyer children also practice.<ref name=\"dar\"/>\n\nWhile a private lawyer, Castriciones also taught at [[Arellano University School of Law]] where he specialized in Corporation Law, Obligations and Contracts, Sales Investment Law, Public and Private International Law and Civil Procedure.<ref name=\"ca\"/> He is also a former lecturer in the Mandatory Continuing Legal Education (MCLE) program of the [[Supreme Court of the Philippines]] for three years.<ref name=\"ca\"/> Castriciones has also authored several books throughout his career, including ''Internal Revolution: Political Vengeance and Societal Perdition'' (2011); ''A Risen Catholic Christian Soldier'' (1998); ''Philippine Military Academy Hazing Case: A General\u2019s Son Dies'' (1990); and ''Sagutin Natin'' (1984).<ref name=\"dar\"/><ref name=\"lbp\"/>\n\nCastriciones entered the government sector in 2009 as Director of the [[Department of Transportation (Philippines)|Department of Transportation]]'s Investigation, Security and Law Enforcement Service (ISLES) under President [[Gloria Macapagal Arroyo]].<ref name=\"dar\"/> He also served as Legal Consultant of the [[Land Transportation Franchising and Regulatory Board]] and as assistant spokesman and deputy chairman of Task Force ''Gabay at Tagapagligtas sa Karagatan'' of the Transportation department.<ref name=\"dar\"/> He was reappointed to the same post in the Transportation department under President [[Benigno Aquino III]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://121.96.41.242/cesbweb%2520(old)/Public%2520Documents/Occupancy%2520Reports/2011/January/DOTC.pdf |title=Department of Transportation and Communications (DOTC) - Career Executive Service Board |publisher=[[Department of Transportation (Philippines)]] |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2016 Philippine presidential election]], Castriciones served as [[PDP-Laban]]'s vice-president for [[Luzon]] who also supported the candidacy of then-mayor of [[Davao City]], [[Rodrigo Duterte]], as president of the Mayor Rodrigo R. Duterte for President Movement (MRRDPM).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bworldonline.com/content.php?section=Nation&title=&145insulted&8217-di&241o-withdraws-pdp-laban-candidacy&id=117820 |title=\u2018Insulted\u2019 Di\u00f1o withdraws PDP-Laban candidacy |publisher=[[BusinessWorld]] |author=Nonato, V. |date=30 October 2015 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> He was eventually appointed by Duterte as Undersecretary of the [[Department of the Interior and Local Government (Philippines)|Department of the Interior and Local Government]] upon his assumption to office.<ref name=\"dar\"/>\n\nIn February 2018, Castriciones helped form the [[Partido Federal ng Pilipinas]] where he currently serves as the party's president. The political party supports the Duterte administration's campaign for a shift to federalism.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manilatimes.net/federal-party-wants-duterte-as-chairman/484386/ |title=Federal party wants Duterte as chairman |publisher=[[The Manila Times]] |author=Pilapil, J. |date=18 December 2018 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> Castriciones, who earlier expressed interest in running for a senatorial post in the [[2019 Philippine Senate election]], announced in October 2018 that he was dropping out of the senatorial race and will be keeping his post as Agrarian Reform secretary.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://businessmirror.com.ph/2018/10/17/castriciones-drops-senatorial-plan-opts-to-keep-dar-post/ |title=Castriciones drops senatorial\u00a0plan, opts to keep DAR post |publisher=[[BusinessMirror]] |author=Mayuga, J. |date=17 October 2018 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=Rosalina Bistoyong (OIC)}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Secretary of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Secretary of Agrarian Reform]]|years=2017\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n|-\n{{s-prec}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Rolando Joselito Bautista]]|as=[[Secretary of Social Welfare and Development (Philippines)|Secretary of Social Welfare and Development]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Philippine order of precedence|Order of Precedence of the Philippines]]<br>{{small|''as [[Secretary of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Secretary of Agrarian Reform]]''}}}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Roy Cimatu]]|as=[[Secretary of Environment and Natural Resources (Philippines)|Secretary of Environment and Natural Resources]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Duterte Cabinet}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Castriciones, John}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Filipino lawyers]]\n[[Category:Filipino male writers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Secretaries of Agrarian Reform of the Philippines]]\n[[Category:San Beda University alumni]]\n[[Category:Arellano University alumni]]\n[[Category:Philippine Military Academy alumni]]\n[[Category:Notre Dame Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Duterte Administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:Benigno Aquino III Administration personnel]]\n[[Category:Arroyo Administration personnel]]\n[[Category:People from Nueva Vizcaya]]\n", "text_old": "{{Philippine name|Rualo|Castriciones}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name = John Castriciones\n| image = John Castriciones 2018 (cropped).jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Castriciones in 2018\n| order = \n| office = 14th [[Secretary of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Secretary of Agrarian Reform of the Philippines]]\n| term_start = December 1, 2017\n| term_end = \n| president = [[Rodrigo Duterte]]\n| predecessor = Rosalina Bistoyong\n| successor =\n| office2 = Undersecretary for Operations of the [[Department of the Interior and Local Government (Philippines)|Department of the Interior and Local Government]]\n| term_start2 = July 1, 2016\n| term_end2 = November 30, 2017\n| president2 = [[Rodrigo Duterte]]\n| predecessor2 = Rafael Santos\n| successor2 = Epimaco V. Densing III\n<!-- personal details -->\n| birth_name = John Rualo Castriciones\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1962|01|08}}\n| birth_place = [[Bayombong]], [[Nueva Vizcaya]], [[Philippines]]\n| nationality = [[Filipino people|Filipino]] \n| party = [[PDP\u2013Laban]]<br>[[Partido Federal ng Pilipinas]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = Lawyer, Professor\n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Trinity University of Asia]] <br> {{small|(AB PolSci)}} <br/>[[Philippine Military Academy]]<br/>[[San Beda University]]<br/>[[Arellano University]] <br> {{small|(LL.B.)}} <br>[[University of Notre Dame]]\n| spouse = \n| children = \n| religion = \n| website = \n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''John Rualo Castriciones''' (born January 8, 1962) is a [[Filipino people|Filipino]] lawyer, public servant and writer who serves as the [[Secretary of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)|Secretary of Agrarian Reform]] of the [[Philippines]] since his appointment by President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] on December 1, 2017.<ref name=\"abs\">{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/12/01/17/duterte-names-dilg-exec-acting-agrarian-reform-chief |title=Duterte names DILG exec acting agrarian reform chief |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Placido, D. |date=1 December 2017 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> He was formerly Undersecretary for Operations of the [[Department of the Interior and Local Government (Philippines)|Department of the Interior and Local Government]] under the same administration.<ref name=\"dar\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dar.gov.ph/about-us/secretary |title=About the Secretary |publisher=[[Department of Agrarian Reform (Philippines)]] |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> A member of the [[Philippine Military Academy]] class of 1994, Castriciones also served in various capacities under two previous administrations and as a law school professor at his alma mater [[Arellano University]].<ref name=\"dar\"/><ref name=\"ca\"/> His appointment to the Agrarian Reform portfolio was approved by the [[Commission on Appointments]] on May 29, 2018, after being bypassed earlier by the commission on March 14, 2018 and reappointed by Duterte on March 22, 2018.<ref name=\"inq\">{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/995299/ca-body-confirms-dar-secretary-castriciones |title=CA body confirms DAR Secretary Castriciones |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Ager, M. |date=29 May 2018 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"pna\">{{cite web|url=https://www.pna.gov.ph/articles/1028644 |title=CA suspends confirmation of DAR Secretary |publisher=[[Philippine News Agency]] |author=Reganit, J.C. |date=14 March 2018 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/11/18/castriciones-reappointed-as-acting-dar-secretary |title=Castriciones reappointed as acting DAR secretary |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Ganibe, D. |date=11 April 2018 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nCastriciones is a native of the province of [[Nueva Vizcaya]]. He was born on January 8, 1962 to a family of farmers in the municipality of [[Bayombong]].<ref name=\"ca\">{{cite web|url=http://comappt.gov.ph/images/pdfiles/newarticle/PressRelease_30May.pdf |title=Cabinet Secretaries Castriciones, Romulo-Puyat, Guevarra, COMELEC Commissioner, DFA senior officials, AFP Chief and ranking officers breeze through the CA |publisher=[[Commission on Appointments]] |date=30 May 2018 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"pna\"/> As a young cadet-student at the [[Philippine Military Academy]] during [[Martial law under Ferdinand Marcos]], Castriciones was accused in the 1981 hazing death of fellow cadet Andres Ramos and was sentenced to five years of hard labor by a seven-man military court in July 1982.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/08/15/world/philippine-military-academy-is-under-attack.html |title=Philippine Military Academy is under attack |publisher=[[The New York Times]] |author=Hollie, P. |date=15 August 1982 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> He was pardoned four year laters by the then newly-installed President [[Corazon Aquino]].<ref name=\"inq2\">{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/996778/http-newsinfo-inquirer-net-995819-poe-endorses-dar-chiefs-appointment-but-vows-to-watch-his-next-steps/amp |title=Courage slams confirmation of Castriciones as DAR chief |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Orellana, F. |date=2 June 2018 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nCastriciones then enrolled at the [[Trinity University of Asia]] in [[Quezon City]], formerly Trinity College, and graduated ''magna cum laude'' with a Political Science degree.<ref name=\"ca\"/> He went on to attend [[San Beda University]], former San Beda College, and [[Arellano University]] to pursue legal studies where he was consistenly in the Dean's List. Castriciones passed the [[Philippine Bar Examination]] in 1990.<ref name=\"dar\"/> He later earned an LL.M. master's degree in Comparative Government and International Law from [[Notre Dame Law School]] in [[London]], U.K. in 1998.<ref name=\"dar\"/><ref name=\"ca\"/>\n\nCastriciones finally completed his military training at the Philippine Military Academy in 1994 as part of the Maharlika Class.<ref name=\"dar\"/>\n\n==Career==\nCastriciones started practicing law in 1993 and has since litigated in both Inferior and Superior Courts, Administrative Bodies, Ombudsman and the [[Sandiganbayan]].<ref name=\"lbp\">{{cite web|url=https://www.landbank.com/node/180 |title=John R. Castriciones |publisher=[[Land Bank of the Philippines]] |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> He served as legal counsel for several corporations and government officials in his more than 20 years of private law practice. Castriciones eventually founded his own law firm, the Castriciones Legal Consultancy, where his lawyer children also practice.<ref name=\"dar\"/>\n\nWhile a private lawyer, Castriciones also taught at [[Arellano University School of Law]] where he specialized in Corporation Law, Obligations and Contracts, Sales Investment Law, Public and Private International Law and Civil Procedure.<ref name=\"ca\"/> He is also a former lecturer in the Mandatory Continuing Legal Education (MCLE) program of the [[Supreme Court of the Philippines]] for three years.<ref name=\"ca\"/> Castriciones has also authored several books throughout his career, including ''Internal Revolution: Political Vengeance and Societal Perdition'' (2011); ''A Risen Catholic Christian Soldier'' (1998); ''Philippine Military Academy Hazing Case: A General\u2019s Son Dies'' (1990); and ''Sagutin Natin'' (1984).<ref name=\"dar\"/><ref name=\"lbp\"/>\n\nCastriciones entered the government sector in 2009 as Director of the [[Department of Transportation (Philippines)|Department of Transportation]]'s Investigation, Security and Law Enforcement Service (ISLES) under President [[Gloria Macapagal Arroyo]].<ref name=\"dar\"/> He also served as Legal Consultant of the [[Land Transportation Franchising and Regulatory Board]] and as assistant spokesman and deputy chairman of Task Force ''Gabay at Tagapagligtas sa Karagatan'' of the Transportation department.<ref name=\"dar\"/> He was reappointed to the same post in the Transportation department under President [[Benigno Aquino III]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://121.96.41.242/cesbweb%2520(old)/Public%2520Documents/Occupancy%2520Reports/2011/January/DOTC.pdf |title=Department of Transportation and Communications (DOTC) - Career Executive Service Board |publisher=[[Department of Transportation (Philippines)]] |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[2016 Philippine presidential election]], Castriciones served as [[PDP-Laban]]'s vice-president for [[Luzon]] who also supported the candidacy of then-mayor of [[Davao City]], [[Rodrigo Duterte]], as president of the Mayor Rodrigo R. Duterte for President Movement (MRRDPM).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bworldonline.com/content.php?section=Nation&title=&145insulted&8217-di&241o-withdraws-pdp-laban-candidacy&id=117820 |title=\u2018Insulted\u2019 Di\u00f1o withdraws PDP-Laban candidacy |publisher=[[BusinessWorld]] |author=Nonato, V. |date=30 October 2015 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> He was eventually appointed by Duterte as Undersecretary of the [[Department of the Interior and Local Government (Philippines)|Department of the Interior and Local Government]] upon his assumption to office.<ref name=\"dar\"/>\n\nIn February 2018, Castriciones helped form the [[Partido Federal ng Pilipinas]] where he currently serves as the party's president. The political party supports the Duterte administration's campaign for a shift to federalism.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manilatimes.net/federal-party-wants-duterte-as-chairman/484386/ |title=Federal party wants Duterte as chairman |publisher=[[The Manila Times]] |author=Pilapil, J. |date=18 December 2018 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref> Castriciones, who earlier expressed interest in running for a senatorial post in the [[2019 Philippine Senate election]], announced in October 2018 that he was dropping out of the senatorial race and will be keeping his post as Agrarian Reform secretary.\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://businessmirror.com.ph/2018/10/17/castriciones-drops-senatorial-plan-opts-to-keep-dar-post/ |title=Castriciones drops senatorial\u00a0plan, opts to keep DAR post |publisher=[[BusinessMirror]] |author=Mayuga, J. |date=17 October 2018 |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n